{"title_page": "Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur (community development block)", "text_new": "{{About|the community development block in West Bengal, India|1 its namesake municipal town|Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|2 its namesake assembly constituency|Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|other places with the same name|Islampur (disambiguation){{!}}Islampur}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Islampur\n| other_name              =  \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = Community development block\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India West Bengal\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in West Bengal, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|26.27|N|88.20|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Uttar Dinajpur district|Uttar Dinajpur]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 329.44\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 300,518\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[English language|English]], [[Urdu]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code             = \n| registration_plate      = \n| blank1_name_sec1        = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1        = [[Raiganj (Lok Sabha constituency)|Raiganj]]\n| blank2_name_sec1        = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1        = [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Islampur]]\n| website                 = {{URL|uttardinajpur.nic.in/}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Islampur''' is a [[Community development block in India|community development block]] that forms an administrative division in [[Islampur subdivision]] of [[Uttar Dinajpur district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[West Bengal]].\n\n==History==\nHistorically the western frontier of ancient [[Pundravardhana]] kingdom, bordering ancient [[Anga]] of Mahabharat fame, the Dinajpur area remained somewhat obscure in the major empires that held sway over the region and beyond till the rise of the Dinajpur Raj during the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] period. Some areas later forming a part of Uttar Dinajpur were parts of kingdoms in Nepal. Dinajpur district was constituted by the [[British Empire|British]] in 1786, with a portion of the estate of Dinajpur Raj. Subsequent to the [[Permanent Settlement]] in 1793, the semi-independent Dinajpur Raj was further broken down and some of its tracts were transferred to the neighbouring British districts of Purnea, Malda, Rajshahi and Bogra. In 1947, the [[Radcliffe Line]] placed the Sadar and Thakurgaon subdivisions of Dinajpur district in East Pakistan. The Balurghat subdivision of Dinajpur district was reconstituted as West Dinajpur district in West Bengal.  Raiganj subdivision was formed in 1948.<ref name=history>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Pages 2-5: Administrative History of Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n \nIn order to restore territorial links between northern and southern parts of West Bengal which had been snapped during the [[Partition of Bengal (1947)|partition of Bengal]], and on the recommendations of the [[States Reorganisation Commission]] a portion of the erstwhile Kishanganj subdivision comprising Goalpokhar, Islampur and Chopra thanas (police stations) and parts of Thakurganj thana, along with the adjacent parts of the erstwhile Gopalpur thana in Katihar subdivision were transferred from Purnea district in Bihar to West Bengal in 1956, and were formally incorporated into Raiganj subdivision in West Dinajpur. The township of [[Kishanganj]] and its entire municipal boundary remained within Bihar. Islampur subdivision was formed in March 1959. At the same time, the portion of Chopra PS lying to the north of the Mahananda river covering an area that now comprises Bidhannagar-1 gram panchayat, Bidhannagar-2 GP, Chathat-Bansgaon GP and the southern half of Phansidewa-Bansgaon Kismat GP in Darjeeling district, was transferred from West Dinajpur to the jurisdiction of Phansidewa PS in Darjeling district. With the introduction of the Community Development Programme in 1960\u201361, community development blocks were set up in West Dinajpur district.<ref name=history/><ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.islampurmunicipality.org/history.php |title =  Islampur Municipality | work=  History |publisher= IM  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, West Dinajpur district was bifurcated and Uttar Dinajpur district was established.<ref name=history/>\n\n==Geography==\nIslampur is located at {{coord|26.27|N|88.20|E|format=dms|}}.\n\nUttar Dinajpur district has a flat topography and slopes gently from north to south. All rivers flow in that direction. Except for the eastern fringes of Chopra CD Block, most of the district is a part of the catchment area of the Mahanada and also a part of the larger [[Barind Tract]] The soil is composed of different varieties of [[alluvium]].  The main rivers are: [[Nagar River (Rangpur)|Nagar]], [[Mahananda River|Mahananda]], Kulik, Gamari, Chhiramati (Srimati) and [[Tangon River|Tangon]]. The rivers have little water in the dry season but with heavy rains, during [[monsoon]], overflow the banks. The Nagar river flows along the international border with Bangladesh on the east of Islampur CD Block. The Sanauna, Dalaucha and Raba rivers flow through Islampur CD Block.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Census of India 2011, Pages 13-14: Physiography, Drainage |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref name=censusmap>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Page 137: Map of Islampur CD Block |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Pages 17-21: The Regional Setting |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIslampur CD Block is bounded by Potha CD Block in [[Kishanganj district]] of Bihar and [[Chopra (community development block)|Chopra]] CD Block on the north, [[Atwari Upazila]] of Panchagarh District of Bangladesh and [[Baliadangi Upazila]] of Thakurgaon District of Bangladesh on the east, [[Goalpokhar I]] CD Block on the south and Kishanganj CD Block in Kishanganj district of Bihar on the west.<ref name=censusmap/><ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 14, Map: Locational Setting of Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url =  https://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/bihar/tehsil/kishanganj.html |title =  CD Block/ Tehsil Map of Kishanganj  |publisher= Maps of India  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nApproximately 206&nbsp;km of the [[Bangladesh-India border|India-Bangladesh border]] is in Uttar Dinajpur district. It covers the eastern boundary of the district. On the western side Uttar Dinajpur district has 227&nbsp;km boundary with Bihar.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://uttardinajpur.nic.in/district_profile.html |title = Egiye Bangla Uttar Dinajpur district  | work= Demographic Profile at a Glance |publisher= Uttar Dinajpur district administration  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIslampur CD Block has an area of 329.44&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.It has 1 [[Panchayat Samiti (Block)|panchayat samity]], 13 [[gram panchayat]]s, 178 gram sansads (village councils), 101 [[mouza]]s and 101 inhabited villages. [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur#Police station|Islampur]] police station serves this block.<ref name=statisticalhandbook1>{{cite web  |url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Statistical%20Handbook |title = District Statistical Handbook 2013 Uttar Dinajpur|work= Tables 2.1, 2.2, 2.3  |publisher = Department of Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal  |accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref> Headquarters of this CD Block is at Islampur.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Map of Uttar Dinajpur district on the fifth page |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web  | url = http://www.wbpublibnet.gov.in/node/2100  | title = BDO Offices under Uttar Dinajpur District  | work = Department of Mass Education Extension & Library Services, Government of West Bengal  | publisher = West Bengal Public Library Network  | accessdate = 26 December 2018  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190119063429/http://wbpublibnet.gov.in/node/2100  | archive-date = 19 January 2019  | url-status = dead  }}</ref>\n\nUttar Dinajpur district is one of the smaller districts in the state and stands 15th in terms of area (3,140.00&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) in the state.<ref name=sizegrowth>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/1904_PART_B_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf | title = Census of India 2011: District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur| work= Series 20, Part XII B, Page 15 | publisher =  Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal |accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Gram panchayat]]s of Islampur block/ panchayat samiti are: Agdimti-Khanti, Gaisal I, Gaisal II, Gobindapur, Gunjaria, Islampur, Kamalagaon-Sujali, Matukunda I, Matikunda II, Panditpota I, Panditpota II, Ramganj I and Ramganj II.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbprd.gov.in/HtmlPage/PANCHAYATS.aspx |title = Directory of District, Subdivision, Panchayat Samiti/ Block and Gram Panchayats in West Bengal |work = Uttar Dinajpur district - Revised in March 2008 | publisher= Panchayats and Rural Development Department, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n===Population===\nAs per the [[2011 Census of India]], Islampur CD Block had a total population of 308,518, all of which were rural. There were 158,933 (52%) males and 149,586 (48%) females. Population below 6 years was 57,788. [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Castes]] numbered 52,418 (16.99%) and [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Tribes]] numbered 8,032 (2.60%).<ref name=census2011>{{cite web| url = http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/cdb_pca_census/Houselisting-housing-WB.html |title = C.D. Block Wise Primary Census Abstract Data(PCA) | work= West Bengal \u2013 District-wise CD Blocks|publisher= Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India  | accessdate = 22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs per 2001 census, Islampur block had a total population of 241,910, out of which 124,368 were males and 117,542 were females. Islampur block registered a population growth of 30.70 per cent during the 1991-2001 decade. Decadal growth for the district was 28.72 per cent<ref name=census>{{cite web|url=http://web.cmc.net.in/wbcensus/DataTables/02/Table4_4.htm |title=Provisional Population Totals, West Bengal , Table 4 |publisher=Census Commissioner of India |work=Census of India 2001, Uttar Dinajpur district (04) |accessdate=2011-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719040124/http://web.cmc.net.in/wbcensus/DataTables/02/Table4_4.htm |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n\nLarge villages (with 4,000+ population) in Islampur CD Block were (2011 population in brackets): Phulhara (11,113), Ramganj (4,660),  Kamlagaon (4,316), Purbba Gomaidighi (11,982), Kuchila (9,549), Dohaso (13,323), Barakhanti (9,617), Agdimti (5,168), Bhojpur (11,055), Panchdimti (9,337), Matikunda (4,529), Phulbari (5,134), Durgapur (4,674), Jagatagaon (6,671), Khabargaon (5,148), Chaprajhar (7,773), Aliganj (4,940), Paschim Pachurasia (7,318), Gunjaria (4,470), Dhantola (9,503), Gaisal (5,954), Kachna (4,809), Birnakundi (6,114), Bhelagachhi (4,528) and Gunabari (11,538).<ref name=census2011/>\n\nOther villages in Islampur CD Block included (2011 population in brackets): Gobindapur (1,110) and Panditpota (3,898).<ref name=census2011/>\n\n'''Decadal [[Population growth|Population Growth]] Rate (%)'''\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|height=200\n|legend=Legend\n|xAxisTitle=X\n|yAxisTitle=Y\n|type= rect\n|x=1971-1981,1981-1991,1991-2001,2001-2011\n|y1 = 28.24,34.08,27.94,27.51\n|y2 = 30.2,34.0,28.7,23.2\n|y3 = 23.17,24.73,17.77,13.93\n|colors = olive,yellow,violet\n|y1Title= Islampur CD Block\n|y2Title= Uttar Dinajpur district\n|y3Title=West Bengal \n}}\n<small>Note: The CD Block data for 1971\u20131981, 1981-1991 and 1991-2001 is for Islampur PS covering the block</small>\n\nThe decadal growth of population in Islampur CD Block in 2001-2011 was 27.51%.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook: Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20  Part XII A  | work= Brief Analysis of Inset Tables based on Primary Census Abstract 2011 (Inset Tables 1-35), Table I: Decadal change in population of Tahsils (Sub-district) by Residence, 2001-2011, Page 47  |publisher=  Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal, 2011 | accessdate = 26 December 2018 }}</ref> The decadal growth of population in Islampur PS  in 1991-2001 was 27.94%, in 1981-91 was 34.08% and in 1971-81 was 28.24%.<ref name=\"humandev1\">{{cite web | url = http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report | title = District Human Development Report, Uttar Dinajpur | work= page 24| publisher =  Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Monitoring, Government of West Bengal |accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref> The decadal growth rate of population in Uttar Dinajpur district was as follows:  30.2% in 1971\u201381, 34.0% in 1981\u201391, 28.7% in 1991-2001 and 23.2% in 2001\u201311.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook: Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20  Part XII A  | work= Page 39: Table 3:  Decadal Growth Rate of Population in Uttar Dinajpur district |publisher=  Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal, 2011 | accessdate = 26 December 2018 }}</ref> The decadal growth rate for West Bengal was 13.93% in 2001\u20132011, 17.77% in 1991\u20132001.<ref name=\"Decadal Growth Rate\">{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/prov_data_products_wb.html | title = Census of India 2011: Provisional Totals for West Bengal  | publisher = Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India  | accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/prov_data_products_wb.html | title = Provisional population totals Paper I: West Bengal | publisher =  Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India |accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref> 24.73% in 1981-1991 and 23.17% in 1971\u20131981.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://wbplan.gov.in/HumanDev/DHDR/24%20pgs%20north.PDF| title = District Human Development Report: North 24 Parganas| work = Page 40, Table 3.2.1| publisher = Development & Planning Department, Government of West Bengal, 2010| accessdate = 26 December 2018| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180205044900/http://wbplan.gov.in/HumanDev/DHDR/24%20pgs%20north.PDF| archive-date = 5 February 2018| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nUttar Dinajpur district has the highest decadal population growth rate in West Bengal with a figure of 23.2% for the decade 2001-2011 and is much higher than the state average of 13.8%.<ref name=sizegrowth/>\n\nAccording to the [[Human Development Report]] for Uttar Dinajpur district, population growth in the area that later became Uttar Dinajpur district was low in the pre-independence era and started picking up with the waves of [[East Bengali refugees]] coming in from erstwhile East Pakistan. Despite the formation of an international border in 1947, none of the PS areas in the area which later formed Islampur SD showed much increase in settlement density between 1941\u201351, and accelerated settlement only came into evidence in this region after 1961, following their transfer from Bihar to West Bengal. Thus, as population growth in the Uttar Dinajpur region accelerated considerably under the impetus of partition migration after 1951, the Islampur SD areas offered additional living space, easing the overall migration pressure on the region.<ref name=population>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 25: Decennial Densist Increment, Pages 292-311: Chapter 6: Migration and Resettlement in Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe Human Development Report analyses, \u201cA spurt in population growth rates first became evident between 1951-1961, and was further magnified between 1971-81 after the creation of Bangladesh when population growth in most districts bordering the Bangladesh-West Bengal frontier showed similar escalation. However, after 1981, when population growth in most other West Bengal districts had tapered off, growth rates in Uttar Dinajpur again showed a fresh spurt. Thus, no deceleration in population growth rates occurred in the district until after 1991\u2026 In addition to [[Illegal immigration in India|Hindu and tribal migrants]] from across the international border, a sizeable number of migrant Muslims have also settled in the district, mainly driven by economic reasons\u2026 migrants from other states comprised 23% of the total migrants residing in Uttar Dinajpur.\u201d The large number of migrants from other states is mainly from the neighbouring areas in Bihar.<ref name=population/>\n\nA study by North Bengal University has observed that \u201cImmigrants from East Pakistan/Bangladesh have arrived in Uttar Dinajpur in almost equal numbers before and after 1971.\u201d The Human Development Report opines, \u201cThe overall post-Partition impact on the rates of demographic growth has been particularly strong in all North Bengal districts. Despite its smaller relative size, the region has received more migration in pro rata terms than the West Bengal districts lying south of the Ganga.\u201d <ref name=population/>\n\n===Literacy===\nAs per the 2011 census, the total number of literates in Islampur CD Block was 134,218 (53.53% of the population over 6 years) out of which males numbered 79,197 (61.14% of the male population over 6 years) and females numbered 55,021 (45.41% of the female population over 6 years). The [[Literacy#Gender disparities|gender disparity]] (the difference between female and male literacy rates) was 15.73%.<ref name=census2011/>\n\nThe [[literacy rate]] in Uttar Dinajpur district at 60.13% in 2011, up from 47.89% in 2001, was the lowest amongst all districts of West Bengal. The highest literacy rate amongst the districts of West Bengal was that of Purba Medinipur district at 87.66% in 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/prov_data_products_wb.html |title = Provisional Population Totals Paper 1 of 2011 : West Bengal | work = Statement-4 Ranking of Districts by Literacy Rate in 2001 and 2011 | publisher =Office of the Registrar General and & Census Commissioner, India, Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |accessdate = 26 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Human Development Report for Uttar Dinajpur district,  \u201cGoalpokhar-1, Goalpokhar-2, Karandighi and Islampur blocks in that order stood at the very bottom of the literacy scale in the state. This pooling of illiteracy within Islampur SD also led to the low ranking of Uttar Dinajpur at 494th position out of 595 Indian districts in terms of literacy rates in 2001, despite which its rank had improved considerably in relative terms from the 523rd rank it had occupied in 1991.\u201d<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 43: Literacy Trends in Uttar Dinajpur district |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe five blocks transferred from the state of Bihar to form a new subdivision in West Dinajpur in 1959 had until 1956 been part of the Kishanganj region which is still characterised by a low overall literacy rate of 31 percent in 2006\u201307, against which the corresponding rate for Uttar Dinajpur as a whole is a literacy rate of 48 percent... \"Like Kishanganj which is now a full-fledged Bihar district, Islampur SD too has a largely rural profile, a large Muslim population and deep concentration of rural poverty\"... Persisting regional disparities in access to education and infrastructure, rather than the response and enthusiasm of the local people are largely responsible for making Uttar Dinajpur the least literate district in West Bengal. \"Thus, a major challenge facing the district relates to the improvement of educational attainments of the weaker social sections and women, especially among the Muslim community which has a dominant presence in the Islampur SD region\u2026 A huge gulf separates the Muslim literacy rate of 36 percent in Uttar Dinajpur from the Muslim literacy rate of 58 percent achieved by West Bengal as a whole.\"<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Pages 83-84: Persisting educational gaps in Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 12 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nSee also \u2013 [[List of West Bengal districts ranked by literacy rate]]\n\nSee also - [[Literacy in Bihar]]\n\n{{Literacy in CD Blocks of Uttar Dinajpur district|collapsible=y}}\n\n===Language and religion===\nIn 2001, [[Bengali language|Bengali]] was the mother-tongue of 66.8% of the population of Uttar Dinajpur district, followed by [[Surajpuri language|Surajpuri]] (11.7%), [[Urdu]] (9.8%), [[Hindi]] (4.0%), [[Santali language|Santali]] (4.0%), Telugu (0.4%), Kurukh/Oraon (0.3%), Bhojpuri (0.3%), Sadan/ Sadri (0.1%), Nepali (0.1%) and Maithili (0.1%). Other languages spoken were: Rajbansi, Oriya, Marwari and Munda. The proportion of population having Bengali as their mother tongue increased from 72.2% in 1961 to 76.5% in 1991 and then dropped to 66.8% in 2001. The proportion of population having Surajpuri as their mother tongue increased from 3.3% in 1991 to 11.7% in 2001. The proportion of population having Urdu as their mother tongue decreased from 10.1% in 1961 to 6.0% in 1971 and then increased to 9.8% in 2001. Information about mother-tongue is available only at the district level and above. In the District Census Handbook for Uttar Dinajpur district covering 2011 census, the mother-tongue information is provided for the period 1961 to 2001.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Census of India 2011, Page 44: Table 11: Mother tongue |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe Human Development Report for Uttar Dinajpur describes the Islampur subdivision as \u201ca region where Urdu and Hindi are widely\nspoken as a first language because of the prior transfer of this territory to West Bengal from Bihar\u201d<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 83 : Persisting educational gaps in Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 12 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAs per the West Bengal Official Language (Amendment) Act, 2012, which came into force from December 2012, Urdu was given the status of official language in areas, such as subdivisions and blocks, having more than 10% Urdu speaking population.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbcmo.gov.in/achieve.aspx?dept=7 |title =  Minority Affairs and Madrasah Education  |publisher=  Chief Minister\u2019s Office, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 14 January 2019 }}</ref> In Uttar Dinajpur district, Goalpokhar I and II blocks, Islampur block and Islampur municipality were identified as fulfilling the norms set<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://zeenews.india.com/news/west-bengal/bengal-gives-second-language-status-to-urdu_756587.html |title = Bengal gives second language status to Urdu |publisher=  Zee News, 4 February 2012 | accessdate = 14 January 2019 }}</ref> In 2014, Calcutta High Court, in an order, included Dalkhola municipality in the list.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://indiankanoon.org/doc/87425337/  |title =  Santosh Chowdhury and Ors Vs State of West Bengal and ors  |publisher= Indian Kanoon  | accessdate = 14 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Islampur CD Block\n|titlebar=#ddd\t\n|left1=\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|Green|72.13}}\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|Orange|27.56}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|Blue|0.25}}\n{{bar percent|Others|Yellow|0.05}}\n}}\t\nIn the 2011 census, Muslims numbered 225,448 and formed 72.13% of the population in Islampur CD Block. Hindus numbered 85,039 and formed 27.56% of the population. Christians numbered 781 and formed 0.25% of the population. Others numbered 150 and formed 0.05% of the population. In Islampur CD Block, as per the District Statistical Handbook for Uttar Dinajpur, while the proportion of Muslims increased from 68.93% in 1991 to 71.08% in 2001, the proportion of Hindus declined from 30.84% in 1991 to 28.69% in 2001.<ref name=censusreligion2011>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/c-01.html |title = C1 Population by Religious Community | work= West Bengal |publisher= Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India  | accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web  | url = http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Statistical%20Handbook   | title = District Statistical Handbook 2013 Uttar Dinajpur  | work = Table 17.1, Population by religion in the blocks of Uttar Dinajpur  | publisher = Department of Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal  | accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2011 census, Uttar Dinajpur district had 1,501,170 Muslims who formed 49.92% of the population, 1,482,943 Hindus who formed 49.31% of the population, 16,702 Christians who formed 0.56% of the population and 6,319 persons belonging to other religions who formed 0.23% of the population. While the proportion of Muslim population in the district increased from 45.3% in 1991 to 49.9% in 2011, the proportion of Hindu population declined from 54.2% in 1991 to 49.2% in 2011.<ref name=censusreligion2011/><ref>{{cite web  | url = http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Statistical%20Handbook   | title = District Statistical Handbook 2013 Uttar Dinajpur  | work = Table 2.10, Population by religion in the district of Murshidabad, 1991 and 2001  | publisher = Department of Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal  | accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Census of India 2011, Pages 43-44: Table 9: Religion |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Rural poverty==\nAs per the Rural Household Survey conducted in 2002, 40.7% of the rural families in Islampur CD Block belonged to the [[Below Poverty Line|BPL]] category, against 46.7% of rural families in Uttar Dinajpur district being in the BPL category.  As per the Human Development Report for Uttar Dinajpur district, Islampur and Karandighi rank sixth and seventh in terms of human development, with respective Human Development Index (HDIs) that indicate the existence of a wide human development gap between them and the lowest ranked Raiganj SD block of Itahar. However, in terms of the concentration of human poverty, they occupy a more favourable position than Itahar.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 358-360: Poverty & Deprivation within Uttar Dinajpur district  |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n===Livelihood===\n{{Pie chart\n|caption= '''Livelihood<br/>in Islampur CD Block'''\n|value1 = 29.36\n|label1 = Cultivators\n|value2 = 40.57\n|label2 = Agricultural labourers\n|value3 = 1.15\n|label3 = Household industries\n|value4 = 28.91 \n|label4 = Other Workers}}\n        \nIn Islampur CD Block in 2011, amongst the class of total workers, cultivators numbered 27,957 and formed 29.36%, agricultural labourers numbered 38,639 and formed  40.57%, household industry workers numbered 1,099 and formed 1.15% and other workers numbered 27,535 and formed 28.91%.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf|title = District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work = Page 66, Table 33: Distribution of Workers by Sex in Four Categories of Economic Activity  in Sub-district 2011 | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 29 December 2018}}</ref> Total workers numbered 95,230 and formed 30.87% of the total population, and non-workers numbered 213,288 and formed 69.13% of the population.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work = Page 62, Table 30: Number and percentage of Main workers, Marginal workers and Non workers by Sex, in Sub-districts, 2011  | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 29 December 2018}}</ref>\n \n<small>Note: In the census records a person is considered a cultivator, if the person is engaged in cultivation/ supervision of land owned by self/government/institution. When a person who works on another person's land for wages in cash or kind or share, is regarded as an agricultural labourer. Household industry is defined as an industry conducted by one or more members of the family within the household or village, and one that does not qualify for registration as a factory under the [[Factories Act,1948, India|Factories Act]]. Other workers are persons engaged in some economic activity other than cultivators, agricultural labourers and household workers.  It includes factory, mining, plantation, transport and office workers, those engaged in business and commerce, teachers, entertainment artistes and so on.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work =  Census Concepts and Definitions, Page 27  | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 29 December 2018}}</ref></small>\n\n===Infrastructure===\nThere are 101 inhabited villages in Islampur CD Block. All 101 villages (100%) have power supply. All 101 villages (100%) have drinking water supply. 17 villages (16.83%) have post offices. 90 villages (89.11%) have telephones (including landlines, public call offices and mobile phones). 42 villages (41.58%) have a pucca (paved) approach road and 20 villages (19.80%) have transport communication (includes bus service, rail facility and navigable waterways). 1 village (0.99%) has an agricultural credit society. 11 villages (10.89%) have banks.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work =  Page 71 Table 36: Distribution of villages according to availability of different amenities, 2011 | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Agriculture===\n\u201cWith its distinctive physiographic and agroclimatic features, the Dinajpur region has been a bread-basket area of Bengal for many centuries, growing multiple varieties of fine and coarse rice in vast quantities, along with major economic crops like jute. The livelihood profile of Uttar Dinajpur district has evolved in association with these old agricultural patterns, and more than two-thirds of its active workforce still draws livelihoods directly from agriculture and related occupations.\u201d<ref name=livelihood>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Pages 143-218: Chapter 4: Economic Livelihood in Uttar Dinajpur district |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 30 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAgricultural potential has been uneven across Uttar Dinajpur based on soil conditions and irrigation potential. This has generated considerable internal migration within the district, as areas with higher agricultural potential and higher labour demand has attracted large number of people. The impact of [[Land reform in India|land reforms]] has also varied. As the Islampur subdivision blocks evolved initially under the Bihar administration, the land estates were larger in size and the extent of land acquired under ceiling laws were higher. The cultivator population in Islampur subdivision was also thinner. Such conditions have been favourable for migrants. The movement of people from agricultural activities to non-agricultural activities has been low in Uttar Dinajpur district except for some pockets.<ref name=livelihood/>\n\nIslampur CD Block had 139 fertiliser depots, 9 seed stores and 63 [[Public distribution system|fair price shops]] in 2013\u201314.<ref name=handbook2014>{{cite web | url = http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Statistical%20Handbook  | title =  District Statistical Handbook 2013 Uttar Dinajpur | work =  Tables 16.1, 18.1, 18.2, 20.1, 21.2, 4.4, 3.1, 3.3 \u2013 arranged as per use | publisher =  Department of Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013\u201314, Islampur CD Block produced 32,426 tonnes of [[Rice#Ecotypes and cultivars|Aman paddy]], the main winter crop from 15,784 hectares, 4,753 tonnes of Boro paddy (spring crop) from 1,917 hectares, 7,072 tonnes of wheat from 3,748 hectares, 3,019 tonnes of maize from 1,240 hectares, 58,719 tonnes of jute from 4,566 hectares and 96,453 tonnes of potatoes from 2,730 hectares. It also produced maskalai and oilseeds.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\nIn 2013\u201314, the total area irrigated in Islampur CD Block was 742 hectares, out of which 450 hectares were irrigated by canal water,12 hectares by river lift irrigation and 280 hectares by deep tube wells.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\n===Craft based activities===\n\u201cMore than eleven hundred rural households across the district are engaged in traditional crafts based industries, among which [[dhokra]], mat making, terracotta, village pottery and bamboo craft in the Goalpokhar-1 and Kaliaganj regions are notable.\u201d<ref name=craft>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 200: Non-farm livelihoods in Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 30 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Banking===\nIn 2012\u201313, Islampur CD Block had offices of 5 commercial banks and 2 [[Regional Rural Bank|gramin banks]].<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\n===Backward Regions Grant Fund===\nUttar Dinajpur district is listed as a backward region and receives financial support from the [[Backward Regions Grant Fund]].  The fund, created by the Government of India, is designed to redress regional imbalances in development. As of 2012, 272 districts across the country were listed under this scheme. The list includes 11 districts of West Bengal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.panchayat.gov.in/documents/10198/0/BRGFFINALGUIDELINES.pdf | title = Backward Regions Grant Funds: Programme Guidelines | publisher = Ministry of Panchayati Raj, Government of India | accessdate = 30 December 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171030225317/http://www.panchayat.gov.in/documents/10198/0/BRGFFINALGUIDELINES.pdf | archive-date = 30 October 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=84879 | title= Backward Regions Grant Fund| work= Press Release, 14 June 2012  |publisher= Press Information  Bureau, Government of India | accessdate =  30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n{{Howrah\u2013New Jalpaiguri line|collapse=yes}}\nIslampur CD Block has 4 ferry services and 10 originating/ terminating bus routes.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\nThe [[Howrah\u2013New Jalpaiguri line]] passes through Islampur CD Block and there are stations \u2013 Aluabari Road Junction, Gunjaria and Gaisal.<ref name=censusmap/><ref>{{cite web| url = https://indiarailinfo.com/train/timetable/malda-town-new-jalpaiguri-passenger-55711/14042/441/444#st | title= 55711/ Malda Town-New Jalpaiguri Passenger| work= Time Table |publisher= indiarailinfo | accessdate =  2 January 2019}}</ref> In the early 1960s, when [[Farakka Barrage]] was being  constructed, a far reaching change was made. Indian Railways constructed a new broad-gauge rail link from south Bengal to connect North Bengal.<ref name=njp>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/docs/rinbad-siliguri.html|title = India: the complex history of the junctions at Siliguri and New Jalpaiguri | publisher= IRFCA|accessdate = 2 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n[[National Highway 27 (India)|National Highway 27]] passes through [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|Islampur]] town and Islampur CD Block.<ref>Google maps</ref>\n\n==Education==\nIn 2012\u201313, Islampur CD Block had 158 primary schools with 35,983 students, 12 middle schools with 2,449 students, 6 high schools with 4,974 students and 18 higher secondary schools with 12,933 students. Islampur CD Block had 1 technical/ professional institution with 47 students and 539 institutions for special and non-formal education with 42,719 students. There is a general degree college in the Islampur municipal area with 6,911 students, outside the CD Block.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\nAs per the 2011 census, in Islampur CD Block, amongst the 101 inhabited villages, 4 villages did not have a school, 59 villages had 1 or more  primary schools, 38 villages had at least 1 primary and 1 middle school and 19 villages had at least 1 middle and 1 secondary school.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1906_PART_A_DCHB_MALDAH.pdf | title = District Census Handbook, Malda, 2011, Series 20, Part XII A | work = Pages 720-21, Appendix I A:  Villages by number of Primary Schools and Appendix I B: Villages by Primary, Middle and Secondary Schools | publisher =  Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal. | accessdate = 30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Midday Meal Scheme|mid-day meal programme]] for rural school children was launched in 2005 in Uttar Dinajpur district. As on 30 April 2015, 602,557 children in 3,006 schools were covered under this programme.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://uttardinajpur.nic.in/middaymeal.html |title = Cooked Mid day meal programme   |publisher= Uttar Dinajpur ditrict administration  | accessdate = 30 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Islampur College]] was established in 1973 at [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|Islampur]] (outside the CD block).<ref>{{cite web| url =  https://www.collegedekho.com/colleges/islampur-college |title = Islampur College  |publisher= College Dekho  | accessdate = 6 January 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.collegeadmission.in/IslampurCollege/Islampur_College.shtml  |title = Islampur College  |publisher=  College Admission | accessdate = 10 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Schools===\n*Ramganj High School at Ramganj \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school>{{cite web| url = https://www.studyapt.com/schools/secondary-schools/islampur-uttar-dinajpur-west-bengal  |title =  Secondary Schools | work=  Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|publisher=  studyapt | accessdate = 10 January 2019 }}</ref>\n*Bhadrakali High School at Gobindapur \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Darivit High School at Panditpota \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/> \n* Jagtagaon High School at Matikunda \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n* Matikunda High School at Matikunda \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Pachhu Rasia High School at Gunjaria \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Patagora High School at Agdimti-Khanti \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Shyama Prasad S. Balika Vidyalaya at Ramganj \u2013 girls only higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Srikrishnapur High School at Matikunda \u2013 coeducationl higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Fazlul Haq N.S. High Madrasah at Agdimti-Khanti -  coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n\n==Healthcare==\nIn 2013, Islampur CD Block had 1 block primary health centre and 1 [[Primary Health Centre (India)|primary health centre]], with total 14 beds and 2 doctors (excluding private bodies). It had 38 family welfare subcentres. 4,862 patients were treated indoor and 238,750 patients were treated outdoor in the hospitals, health centres and subcentres of the CD Block.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\nIslampur subdivisional hospital  at [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|Islampur]] (with 136 beds) is located outside the Islampur CD block. There is a  [[Primary Health Centre (India)|primary health centre]] at Sujali (with 4 beds).<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wbhealth.gov.in/ | title = Health & Family Welfare Department | work= Health Statistics | publisher = Government of West Bengal  |accessdate =  12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Raiganj}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n{{Municipalities of West Bengal}}\n{{Uttar Dinajpur topics}}\n\n[[Category:Community development blocks in Uttar Dinajpur district]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the community development block in West Bengal, India|1 its namesake municipal town|Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|2 its namesake assembly constituency|Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|other places with the same name|Islampur (disambiguation){{!}}Islampur}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                    = Islampur\n| other_name              =  \n| nickname                = \n| settlement_type         = Community development block\n| image_skyline           = \n| image_alt               = \n| image_caption           = \n| pushpin_map             = India West Bengal\n| pushpin_label_position  = right\n| pushpin_map_alt         = \n| pushpin_map_caption     = Location in West Bengal, India\n| coordinates             = {{coord|26.27|N|88.20|E|display=inline,title}}\n| subdivision_type        = Country\n| subdivision_name        = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1       = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[West Bengal]]\n| subdivision_type2       = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2       = [[Uttar Dinajpur district|Uttar Dinajpur]]\n| established_title       = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date        = \n| founder                 = \n| named_for               = \n| government_type         = \n| governing_body          = \n| unit_pref               = Metric\n| area_footnotes          = \n| area_rank               = \n| area_total_km2          = 329.44\n| elevation_footnotes     = \n| elevation_m             = \n| population_total        = 300,518\n| population_as_of        = 2011\n| population_rank         = \n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      = \n| population_footnotes    = \n| demographics_type1      = Languages\n| demographics1_title1    = Official\n| demographics1_info1     = [[Bengali language|Bengali]], [[English language|English]], [[Urdu]]\n| timezone1               = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1             = +5:30\n| postal_code_type        = <!-- [[Postal Index Number|PIN]] -->\n| postal_code             = \n| registration_plate      = \n| blank1_name_sec1        = [[Lok Sabha]] constituency\n| blank1_info_sec1        = [[Raiganj (Lok Sabha constituency)|Raiganj]]\n| blank2_name_sec1        = [[Vidhan Sabha]] constituency\n| blank2_info_sec1        = [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur (Vidhan Sabha constituency)|Islampur]]\n| website                 = {{URL|uttardinajpur.nic.in/}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}\n'''Islampur''' is a [[Community development block in India|community development block]] that forms an administrative division in [[Islampur subdivision]] of [[Uttar Dinajpur district]] in the [[India]]n [[States and territories of India|state]] of [[West Bengal]].\n\n==History==\nHistorically the western frontier of ancient [[Pundravardhana]] kingdom, bordering ancient [[Anga]] of Mahabharat fame, the Dinajpur area remained somewhat obscure in the major empires that held sway over the region and beyond till the rise of the Dinajpur Raj during the [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] period. Some areas later forming a part of Uttar Dinajpur were parts of kingdoms in Nepal. Dinajpur district was constituted by the [[British Empire|British]] in 1786, with a portion of the estate of Dinajpur Raj. Subsequent to the [[Permanent Settlement]] in 1793, the semi-independent Dinajpur Raj was further broken down and some of its tracts were transferred to the neighbouring British districts of Purnea, Malda, Rajshahi and Bogra. In 1947, the [[Radcliffe Line]] placed the Sadar and Thakurgaon subdivisions of Dinajpur district in East Pakistan. The Balurghat subdivision of Dinajpur district was reconstituted as West Dinajpur district in West Bengal.  Raiganj subdivision was formed in 1948.<ref name=history>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Pages 2-5: Administrative History of Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n \nIn order to restore territorial links between northern and southern parts of West Bengal which had been snapped during the [[Partition of Bengal (1947)|partition of Bengal]], and on the recommendations of the [[States Reorganisation Commission]] a portion of the erstwhile Kishanganj subdivision comprising Goalpokhar, Islampur and Chopra thanas (police stations) and parts of Thakurganj thana, along with the adjacent parts of the erstwhile Gopalpur thana in Katihar subdivision were transferred from Purnea district in Bihar to West Bengal in 1956, and were formally incorporated into Raiganj subdivision in West Dinajpur. The township of [[Kishanganj]] and its entire municipal boundary remained within Bihar. Islampur subdivision was formed in March 1959. At the same time, the portion of Chopra PS lying to the north of the Mahananda river covering an area that now comprises Bidhannagar-1 gram panchayat, Bidhannagar-2 GP, Chathat-Bansgaon GP and the southern half of Phansidewa-Bansgaon Kismat GP in Darjeeling district, was transferred from West Dinajpur to the jurisdiction of Phansidewa PS in Darjeling district. With the introduction of the Community Development Programme in 1960-61, community development blocks were set up in West Dinajpur district.<ref name=history/><ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.islampurmunicipality.org/history.php |title =  Islampur Municipality | work=  History |publisher= IM  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIn 1992, West Dinajpur district was bifurcated and Uttar Dinajpur district was established.<ref name=history/>\n\n==Geography==\nIslampur is located at {{coord|26.27|N|88.20|E|format=dms|}}.\n\nUttar Dinajpur district has a flat topography and slopes gently from north to south. All rivers flow in that direction. Except for the eastern fringes of Chopra CD Block, most of the district is a part of the catchment area of the Mahanada and also a part of the larger [[Barind Tract]] The soil is composed of different varieties of [[alluvium]].  The main rivers are: [[Nagar River (Rangpur)|Nagar]], [[Mahananda River|Mahananda]], Kulik, Gamari, Chhiramati (Srimati) and [[Tangon River|Tangon]]. The rivers have little water in the dry season but with heavy rains, during [[monsoon]], overflow the banks. The Nagar river flows along the international border with Bangladesh on the east of Islampur CD Block. The Sanauna, Dalaucha and Raba rivers flow through Islampur CD Block.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Census of India 2011, Pages 13-14: Physiography, Drainage |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref name=censusmap>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Page 137: Map of Islampur CD Block |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Pages 17-21: The Regional Setting |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIslampur CD Block is bounded by Potha CD Block in [[Kishanganj district]] of Bihar and [[Chopra (community development block)|Chopra]] CD Block on the north, [[Atwari Upazila]] of Panchagarh District of Bangladesh and [[Baliadangi Upazila]] of Thakurgaon District of Bangladesh on the east, [[Goalpokhar I]] CD Block on the south and Kishanganj CD Block in Kishanganj district of Bihar on the west.<ref name=censusmap/><ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 14, Map: Locational Setting of Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url =  https://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/bihar/tehsil/kishanganj.html |title =  CD Block/ Tehsil Map of Kishanganj  |publisher= Maps of India  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nApproximately 206&nbsp;km of the [[Bangladesh-India border|India-Bangladesh border]] is in Uttar Dinajpur district. It covers the eastern boundary of the district. On the western side Uttar Dinajpur district has 227&nbsp;km boundary with Bihar.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://uttardinajpur.nic.in/district_profile.html |title = Egiye Bangla Uttar Dinajpur district  | work= Demographic Profile at a Glance |publisher= Uttar Dinajpur district administration  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nIslampur CD Block has an area of 329.44&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>.It has 1 [[Panchayat Samiti (Block)|panchayat samity]], 13 [[gram panchayat]]s, 178 gram sansads (village councils), 101 [[mouza]]s and 101 inhabited villages. [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur#Police station|Islampur]] police station serves this block.<ref name=statisticalhandbook1>{{cite web  |url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Statistical%20Handbook |title = District Statistical Handbook 2013 Uttar Dinajpur|work= Tables 2.1, 2.2, 2.3  |publisher = Department of Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal  |accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref> Headquarters of this CD Block is at Islampur.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Map of Uttar Dinajpur district on the fifth page |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web  | url = http://www.wbpublibnet.gov.in/node/2100  | title = BDO Offices under Uttar Dinajpur District  | work = Department of Mass Education Extension & Library Services, Government of West Bengal  | publisher = West Bengal Public Library Network  | accessdate = 26 December 2018  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190119063429/http://wbpublibnet.gov.in/node/2100  | archive-date = 19 January 2019  | url-status = dead  }}</ref>\n\nUttar Dinajpur district is one of the smaller districts in the state and stands 15th in terms of area (3,140.00&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup>) in the state.<ref name=sizegrowth>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/1904_PART_B_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf | title = Census of India 2011: District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur| work= Series 20, Part XII B, Page 15 | publisher =  Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal |accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Gram panchayat]]s of Islampur block/ panchayat samiti are: Agdimti-Khanti, Gaisal I, Gaisal II, Gobindapur, Gunjaria, Islampur, Kamalagaon-Sujali, Matukunda I, Matikunda II, Panditpota I, Panditpota II, Ramganj I and Ramganj II.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbprd.gov.in/HtmlPage/PANCHAYATS.aspx |title = Directory of District, Subdivision, Panchayat Samiti/ Block and Gram Panchayats in West Bengal |work = Uttar Dinajpur district - Revised in March 2008 | publisher= Panchayats and Rural Development Department, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 1 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\n===Population===\nAs per the [[2011 Census of India]], Islampur CD Block had a total population of 308,518, all of which were rural. There were 158,933 (52%) males and 149,586 (48%) females. Population below 6 years was 57,788. [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Castes]] numbered 52,418 (16.99%) and [[Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes|Scheduled Tribes]] numbered 8,032 (2.60%).<ref name=census2011>{{cite web| url = http://censusindia.gov.in/pca/cdb_pca_census/Houselisting-housing-WB.html |title = C.D. Block Wise Primary Census Abstract Data(PCA) | work= West Bengal \u2013 District-wise CD Blocks|publisher= Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India  | accessdate = 22 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs per 2001 census, Islampur block had a total population of 241,910, out of which 124,368 were males and 117,542 were females. Islampur block registered a population growth of 30.70 per cent during the 1991-2001 decade. Decadal growth for the district was 28.72 per cent<ref name=census>{{cite web|url=http://web.cmc.net.in/wbcensus/DataTables/02/Table4_4.htm |title=Provisional Population Totals, West Bengal , Table 4 |publisher=Census Commissioner of India |work=Census of India 2001, Uttar Dinajpur district (04) |accessdate=2011-03-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110719040124/http://web.cmc.net.in/wbcensus/DataTables/02/Table4_4.htm |archivedate=2011-07-19 }}</ref>\n\nLarge villages (with 4,000+ population) in Islampur CD Block were (2011 population in brackets): Phulhara (11,113), Ramganj (4,660),  Kamlagaon (4,316), Purbba Gomaidighi (11,982), Kuchila (9,549), Dohaso (13,323), Barakhanti (9,617), Agdimti (5,168), Bhojpur (11,055), Panchdimti (9,337), Matikunda (4,529), Phulbari (5,134), Durgapur (4,674), Jagatagaon (6,671), Khabargaon (5,148), Chaprajhar (7,773), Aliganj (4,940), Paschim Pachurasia (7,318), Gunjaria (4,470), Dhantola (9,503), Gaisal (5,954), Kachna (4,809), Birnakundi (6,114), Bhelagachhi (4,528) and Gunabari (11,538).<ref name=census2011/>\n\nOther villages in Islampur CD Block included (2011 population in brackets): Gobindapur (1,110) and Panditpota (3,898).<ref name=census2011/>\n\n'''Decadal [[Population growth|Population Growth]] Rate (%)'''\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width=300\n|height=200\n|legend=Legend\n|xAxisTitle=X\n|yAxisTitle=Y\n|type= rect\n|x=1971-1981,1981-1991,1991-2001,2001-2011\n|y1 = 28.24,34.08,27.94,27.51\n|y2 = 30.2,34.0,28.7,23.2\n|y3 = 23.17,24.73,17.77,13.93\n|colors = olive,yellow,violet\n|y1Title= Islampur CD Block\n|y2Title= Uttar Dinajpur district\n|y3Title=West Bengal \n}}\n<small>Note: The CD Block data for 1971-1981, 1981-1991 and 1991-2001 is for Islampur PS covering the block</small>\n\nThe decadal growth of population in Islampur CD Block in 2001-2011 was 27.51%.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook: Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20  Part XII A  | work= Brief Analysis of Inset Tables based on Primary Census Abstract 2011 (Inset Tables 1-35), Table I: Decadal change in population of Tahsils (Sub-district) by Residence, 2001-2011, Page 47  |publisher=  Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal, 2011 | accessdate = 26 December 2018 }}</ref> The decadal growth of population in Islampur PS  in 1991-2001 was 27.94%, in 1981-91 was 34.08% and in 1971-81 was 28.24%.<ref name=\"humandev1\">{{cite web | url = http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report | title = District Human Development Report, Uttar Dinajpur | work= page 24| publisher =  Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Monitoring, Government of West Bengal |accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref> The decadal growth rate of population in Uttar Dinajpur district was as follows:  30.2% in 1971-81, 34.0% in 1981-91, 28.7% in 1991-2001 and 23.2% in 2001-11.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook: Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20  Part XII A  | work= Page 39: Table 3:  Decadal Growth Rate of Population in Uttar Dinajpur district |publisher=  Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal, 2011 | accessdate = 26 December 2018 }}</ref> The decadal growth rate for West Bengal was 13.93% in 2001-2011, 17.77% in 1991-2001.<ref name=\"Decadal Growth Rate\">{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/prov_data_products_wb.html | title = Census of India 2011: Provisional Totals for West Bengal  | publisher = Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India  | accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/prov_data_products_wb.html | title = Provisional population totals Paper I: West Bengal | publisher =  Registrar General and Census Commissioner of India |accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref> 24.73% in 1981-1991 and 23.17% in 1971-1981.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://wbplan.gov.in/HumanDev/DHDR/24%20pgs%20north.PDF| title = District Human Development Report: North 24 Parganas| work = Page 40, Table 3.2.1| publisher = Development & Planning Department, Government of West Bengal, 2010| accessdate = 26 December 2018| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180205044900/http://wbplan.gov.in/HumanDev/DHDR/24%20pgs%20north.PDF| archive-date = 5 February 2018| url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nUttar Dinajpur district has the highest decadal population growth rate in West Bengal with a figure of 23.2% for the decade 2001-2011 and is much higher than the state average of 13.8%.<ref name=sizegrowth/>\n\nAccording to the [[Human Development Report]] for Uttar Dinajpur district, population growth in the area that later became Uttar Dinajpur district was low in the pre-independence era and started picking up with the waves of [[East Bengali refugees]] coming in from erstwhile East Pakistan. Despite the formation of an international border in 1947, none of the PS areas in the area which later formed Islampur SD showed much increase in settlement density between 1941\u201351, and accelerated settlement only came into evidence in this region after 1961, following their transfer from Bihar to West Bengal. Thus, as population growth in the Uttar Dinajpur region accelerated considerably under the impetus of partition migration after 1951, the Islampur SD areas offered additional living space, easing the overall migration pressure on the region.<ref name=population>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 25: Decennial Densist Increment, Pages 292-311: Chapter 6: Migration and Resettlement in Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe Human Development Report analyses, \u201cA spurt in population growth rates first became evident between 1951-1961, and was further magnified between 1971-81 after the creation of Bangladesh when population growth in most districts bordering the Bangladesh-West Bengal frontier showed similar escalation. However, after 1981, when population growth in most other West Bengal districts had tapered off, growth rates in Uttar Dinajpur again showed a fresh spurt. Thus, no deceleration in population growth rates occurred in the district until after 1991\u2026 In addition to [[Illegal immigration in India|Hindu and tribal migrants]] from across the international border, a sizeable number of migrant Muslims have also settled in the district, mainly driven by economic reasons\u2026 migrants from other states comprised 23% of the total migrants residing in Uttar Dinajpur.\u201d The large number of migrants from other states is mainly from the neighbouring areas in Bihar.<ref name=population/>\n\nA study by North Bengal University has observed that \u201cImmigrants from East Pakistan/Bangladesh have arrived in Uttar Dinajpur in almost equal numbers before and after 1971.\u201d The Human Development Report opines, \u201cThe overall post-Partition impact on the rates of demographic growth has been particularly strong in all North Bengal districts. Despite its smaller relative size, the region has received more migration in pro rata terms than the West Bengal districts lying south of the Ganga.\u201d <ref name=population/>\n\n===Literacy===\nAs per the 2011 census, the total number of literates in Islampur CD Block was 134,218 (53.53% of the population over 6 years) out of which males numbered 79,197 (61.14% of the male population over 6 years) and females numbered 55,021 (45.41% of the female population over 6 years). The [[Literacy#Gender disparities|gender disparity]] (the difference between female and male literacy rates) was 15.73%.<ref name=census2011/>\n\nThe [[literacy rate]] in Uttar Dinajpur district at 60.13% in 2011, up from 47.89% in 2001, was the lowest amongst all districts of West Bengal. The highest literacy rate amongst the districts of West Bengal was that of Purba Medinipur district at 87.66% in 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/prov_data_products_wb.html |title = Provisional Population Totals Paper 1 of 2011 : West Bengal | work = Statement-4 Ranking of Districts by Literacy Rate in 2001 and 2011 | publisher =Office of the Registrar General and & Census Commissioner, India, Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |accessdate = 26 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Human Development Report for Uttar Dinajpur district,  \u201cGoalpokhar-1, Goalpokhar-2, Karandighi and Islampur blocks in that order stood at the very bottom of the literacy scale in the state. This pooling of illiteracy within Islampur SD also led to the low ranking of Uttar Dinajpur at 494th position out of 595 Indian districts in terms of literacy rates in 2001, despite which its rank had improved considerably in relative terms from the 523rd rank it had occupied in 1991.\u201d<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 43: Literacy Trends in Uttar Dinajpur district |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe five blocks transferred from the state of Bihar to form a new subdivision in West Dinajpur in 1959 had until 1956 been part of the Kishanganj region which is still characterised by a low overall literacy rate of 31 percent in 2006-07, against which the corresponding rate for Uttar Dinajpur as a whole is a literacy rate of 48 percent... \"Like Kishanganj which is now a full-fledged Bihar district, Islampur SD too has a largely rural profile, a large Muslim population and deep concentration of rural poverty\"... Persisting regional disparities in access to education and infrastructure, rather than the response and enthusiasm of the local people are largely responsible for making Uttar Dinajpur the least literate district in West Bengal. \"Thus, a major challenge facing the district relates to the improvement of educational attainments of the weaker social sections and women, especially among the Muslim community which has a dominant presence in the Islampur SD region\u2026 A huge gulf separates the Muslim literacy rate of 36 percent in Uttar Dinajpur from the Muslim literacy rate of 58 percent achieved by West Bengal as a whole.\"<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Pages 83-84: Persisting educational gaps in Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 12 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nSee also \u2013 [[List of West Bengal districts ranked by literacy rate]]\n\nSee also - [[Literacy in Bihar]]\n\n{{Literacy in CD Blocks of Uttar Dinajpur district|collapsible=y}}\n\n===Language and religion===\nIn 2001, [[Bengali language|Bengali]] was the mother-tongue of 66.8% of the population of Uttar Dinajpur district, followed by [[Surajpuri language|Surajpuri]] (11.7%), [[Urdu]] (9.8%), [[Hindi]] (4.0%), [[Santali language|Santali]] (4.0%), Telugu (0.4%), Kurukh/Oraon (0.3%), Bhojpuri (0.3%), Sadan/ Sadri (0.1%), Nepali (0.1%) and Maithili (0.1%). Other languages spoken were: Rajbansi, Oriya, Marwari and Munda. The proportion of population having Bengali as their mother tongue increased from 72.2% in 1961 to 76.5% in 1991 and then dropped to 66.8% in 2001. The proportion of population having Surajpuri as their mother tongue increased from 3.3% in 1991 to 11.7% in 2001. The proportion of population having Urdu as their mother tongue decreased from 10.1% in 1961 to 6.0% in 1971 and then increased to 9.8% in 2001. Information about mother-tongue is available only at the district level and above. In the District Census Handbook for Uttar Dinajpur district covering 2011 census, the mother-tongue information is provided for the period 1961 to 2001.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Census of India 2011, Page 44: Table 11: Mother tongue |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nThe Human Development Report for Uttar Dinajpur describes the Islampur subdivision as \u201ca region where Urdu and Hindi are widely\nspoken as a first language because of the prior transfer of this territory to West Bengal from Bihar\u201d<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 83 : Persisting educational gaps in Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 12 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\nAs per the West Bengal Official Language (Amendment) Act, 2012, which came into force from December 2012, Urdu was given the status of official language in areas, such as subdivisions and blocks, having more than 10% Urdu speaking population.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbcmo.gov.in/achieve.aspx?dept=7 |title =  Minority Affairs and Madrasah Education  |publisher=  Chief Minister\u2019s Office, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 14 January 2019 }}</ref> In Uttar Dinajpur district, Goalpokhar I and II blocks, Islampur block and Islampur municipality were identified as fulfilling the norms set<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://zeenews.india.com/news/west-bengal/bengal-gives-second-language-status-to-urdu_756587.html |title = Bengal gives second language status to Urdu |publisher=  Zee News, 4 February 2012 | accessdate = 14 January 2019 }}</ref> In 2014, Calcutta High Court, in an order, included Dalkhola municipality in the list.<ref>{{cite web| url = https://indiankanoon.org/doc/87425337/  |title =  Santosh Chowdhury and Ors Vs State of West Bengal and ors  |publisher= Indian Kanoon  | accessdate = 14 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n{{bar box\n|title=Religion in Islampur CD Block\n|titlebar=#ddd\t\n|left1=\n|float=right\n|bars=\n{{bar percent|[[Muslims]]|Green|72.13}}\n{{bar percent|[[Hindus]]|Orange|27.56}}\n{{bar percent|[[Christians]]|Blue|0.25}}\n{{bar percent|Others|Yellow|0.05}}\n}}\t\nIn the 2011 census, Muslims numbered 225,448 and formed 72.13% of the population in Islampur CD Block. Hindus numbered 85,039 and formed 27.56% of the population. Christians numbered 781 and formed 0.25% of the population. Others numbered 150 and formed 0.05% of the population. In Islampur CD Block, as per the District Statistical Handbook for Uttar Dinajpur, while the proportion of Muslims increased from 68.93% in 1991 to 71.08% in 2001, the proportion of Hindus declined from 30.84% in 1991 to 28.69% in 2001.<ref name=censusreligion2011>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/c-01.html |title = C1 Population by Religious Community | work= West Bengal |publisher= Registrar General and Census Commissioner, India  | accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web  | url = http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Statistical%20Handbook   | title = District Statistical Handbook 2013 Uttar Dinajpur  | work = Table 17.1, Population by religion in the blocks of Uttar Dinajpur  | publisher = Department of Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal  | accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2011 census, Uttar Dinajpur district had 1,501,170 Muslims who formed 49.92% of the population, 1,482,943 Hindus who formed 49.31% of the population, 16,702 Christians who formed 0.56% of the population and 6,319 persons belonging to other religions who formed 0.23% of the population. While the proportion of Muslim population in the district increased from 45.3% in 1991 to 49.9% in 2011, the proportion of Hindu population declined from 54.2% in 1991 to 49.2% in 2011.<ref name=censusreligion2011/><ref>{{cite web  | url = http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Statistical%20Handbook   | title = District Statistical Handbook 2013 Uttar Dinajpur  | work = Table 2.10, Population by religion in the district of Murshidabad, 1991 and 2001  | publisher = Department of Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal  | accessdate = 26 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url =  http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title =  District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Series 20, Part XII A | work= Census of India 2011, Pages 43-44: Table 9: Religion |publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal  | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Rural poverty==\nAs per the Rural Household Survey conducted in 2002, 40.7% of the rural families in Islampur CD Block belonged to the [[Below Poverty Line|BPL]] category, against 46.7% of rural families in Uttar Dinajpur district being in the BPL category.  As per the Human Development Report for Uttar Dinajpur district, Islampur and Karandighi rank sixth and seventh in terms of human development, with respective Human Development Index (HDIs) that indicate the existence of a wide human development gap between them and the lowest ranked Raiganj SD block of Itahar. However, in terms of the concentration of human poverty, they occupy a more favourable position than Itahar.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 358-360: Poverty & Deprivation within Uttar Dinajpur district  |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 24 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n==Economy==\n===Livelihood===\n{{Pie chart\n|caption= '''Livelihood<br/>in Islampur CD Block'''\n|value1 = 29.36\n|label1 = Cultivators\n|value2 = 40.57\n|label2 = Agricultural labourers\n|value3 = 1.15\n|label3 = Household industries\n|value4 = 28.91 \n|label4 = Other Workers}}\n        \nIn Islampur CD Block in 2011, amongst the class of total workers, cultivators numbered 27,957 and formed 29.36%, agricultural labourers numbered 38,639 and formed  40.57%, household industry workers numbered 1,099 and formed 1.15% and other workers numbered 27,535 and formed 28.91%.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf|title = District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work = Page 66, Table 33: Distribution of Workers by Sex in Four Categories of Economic Activity  in Sub-district 2011 | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 29 December 2018}}</ref> Total workers numbered 95,230 and formed 30.87% of the total population, and non-workers numbered 213,288 and formed 69.13% of the population.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work = Page 62, Table 30: Number and percentage of Main workers, Marginal workers and Non workers by Sex, in Sub-districts, 2011  | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 29 December 2018}}</ref>\n \n<small>Note: In the census records a person is considered a cultivator, if the person is engaged in cultivation/ supervision of land owned by self/government/institution. When a person who works on another person's land for wages in cash or kind or share, is regarded as an agricultural labourer. Household industry is defined as an industry conducted by one or more members of the family within the household or village, and one that does not qualify for registration as a factory under the [[Factories Act,1948, India|Factories Act]]. Other workers are persons engaged in some economic activity other than cultivators, agricultural labourers and household workers.  It includes factory, mining, plantation, transport and office workers, those engaged in business and commerce, teachers, entertainment artistes and so on.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work =  Census Concepts and Definitions, Page 27  | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 29 December 2018}}</ref></small>\n\n===Infrastructure===\nThere are 101 inhabited villages in Islampur CD Block. All 101 villages (100%) have power supply. All 101 villages (100%) have drinking water supply. 17 villages (16.83%) have post offices. 90 villages (89.11%) have telephones (including landlines, public call offices and mobile phones). 42 villages (41.58%) have a pucca (paved) approach road and 20 villages (19.80%) have transport communication (includes bus service, rail facility and navigable waterways). 1 village (0.99%) has an agricultural credit society. 11 villages (10.89%) have banks.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1904_PART_A_DCHB_UTTAR%20DINAJPUR.pdf |title = District Census Handbook Uttar Dinajpur, Census of India 2011, Series 20, Part XII A |work =  Page 71 Table 36: Distribution of villages according to availability of different amenities, 2011 | publisher= Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal| accessdate = 29 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Agriculture===\n\u201cWith its distinctive physiographic and agroclimatic features, the Dinajpur region has been a bread-basket area of Bengal for many centuries, growing multiple varieties of fine and coarse rice in vast quantities, along with major economic crops like jute. The livelihood profile of Uttar Dinajpur district has evolved in association with these old agricultural patterns, and more than two-thirds of its active workforce still draws livelihoods directly from agriculture and related occupations.\u201d<ref name=livelihood>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Pages 143-218: Chapter 4: Economic Livelihood in Uttar Dinajpur district |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 30 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAgricultural potential has been uneven across Uttar Dinajpur based on soil conditions and irrigation potential. This has generated considerable internal migration within the district, as areas with higher agricultural potential and higher labour demand has attracted large number of people. The impact of [[Land reform in India|land reforms]] has also varied. As the Islampur subdivision blocks evolved initially under the Bihar administration, the land estates were larger in size and the extent of land acquired under ceiling laws were higher. The cultivator population in Islampur subdivision was also thinner. Such conditions have been favourable for migrants. The movement of people from agricultural activities to non-agricultural activities has been low in Uttar Dinajpur district except for some pockets.<ref name=livelihood/>\n\nIslampur CD Block had 139 fertiliser depots, 9 seed stores and 63 [[Public distribution system|fair price shops]] in 2013-14.<ref name=handbook2014>{{cite web | url = http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Statistical%20Handbook  | title =  District Statistical Handbook 2013 Uttar Dinajpur | work =  Tables 16.1, 18.1, 18.2, 20.1, 21.2, 4.4, 3.1, 3.3 \u2013 arranged as per use | publisher =  Department of Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013-14, Islampur CD Block produced 32,426 tonnes of [[Rice#Ecotypes and cultivars|Aman paddy]], the main winter crop from 15,784 hectares, 4,753 tonnes of Boro paddy (spring crop) from 1,917 hectares, 7,072 tonnes of wheat from 3,748 hectares, 3,019 tonnes of maize from 1,240 hectares, 58,719 tonnes of jute from 4,566 hectares and 96,453 tonnes of potatoes from 2,730 hectares. It also produced maskalai and oilseeds.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\nIn 2013-14, the total area irrigated in Islampur CD Block was 742 hectares, out of which 450 hectares were irrigated by canal water,12 hectares by river lift irrigation and 280 hectares by deep tube wells.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\n===Craft based activities===\n\u201cMore than eleven hundred rural households across the district are engaged in traditional crafts based industries, among which [[dhokra]], mat making, terracotta, village pottery and bamboo craft in the Goalpokhar-1 and Kaliaganj regions are notable.\u201d<ref name=craft>{{cite web| url =  http://wbpspm.gov.in/publications/District%20Human%20Development%20Report |title =  District Human Development Report  | work=  Uttar Dinajpur. Page 200: Non-farm livelihoods in Uttar Dinajpur |publisher= Department of Planning, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Government of West Bengal | accessdate = 30 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n===Banking===\nIn 2012-13, Islampur CD Block had offices of 5 commercial banks and 2 [[Regional Rural Bank|gramin banks]].<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\n===Backward Regions Grant Fund===\nUttar Dinajpur district is listed as a backward region and receives financial support from the [[Backward Regions Grant Fund]].  The fund, created by the Government of India, is designed to redress regional imbalances in development. As of 2012, 272 districts across the country were listed under this scheme. The list includes 11 districts of West Bengal.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.panchayat.gov.in/documents/10198/0/BRGFFINALGUIDELINES.pdf | title = Backward Regions Grant Funds: Programme Guidelines | publisher = Ministry of Panchayati Raj, Government of India | accessdate = 30 December 2018 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171030225317/http://www.panchayat.gov.in/documents/10198/0/BRGFFINALGUIDELINES.pdf | archive-date = 30 October 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=84879 | title= Backward Regions Grant Fund| work= Press Release, 14 June 2012  |publisher= Press Information  Bureau, Government of India | accessdate =  30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Transport==\n{{Howrah\u2013New Jalpaiguri line|collapse=yes}}\nIslampur CD Block has 4 ferry services and 10 originating/ terminating bus routes.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\nThe [[Howrah\u2013New Jalpaiguri line]] passes through Islampur CD Block and there are stations \u2013 Aluabari Road Junction, Gunjaria and Gaisal.<ref name=censusmap/><ref>{{cite web| url = https://indiarailinfo.com/train/timetable/malda-town-new-jalpaiguri-passenger-55711/14042/441/444#st | title= 55711/ Malda Town-New Jalpaiguri Passenger| work= Time Table |publisher= indiarailinfo | accessdate =  2 January 2019}}</ref> In the early 1960s, when [[Farakka Barrage]] was being  constructed, a far reaching change was made. Indian Railways constructed a new broad-gauge rail link from south Bengal to connect North Bengal.<ref name=njp>{{cite web| url = http://www.irfca.org/docs/rinbad-siliguri.html|title = India: the complex history of the junctions at Siliguri and New Jalpaiguri | publisher= IRFCA|accessdate = 2 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n[[National Highway 27 (India)|National Highway 27]] passes through [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|Islampur]] town and Islampur CD Block.<ref>Google maps</ref>\n\n==Education==\nIn 2012-13, Islampur CD Block had 158 primary schools with 35,983 students, 12 middle schools with 2,449 students, 6 high schools with 4,974 students and 18 higher secondary schools with 12,933 students. Islampur CD Block had 1 technical/ professional institution with 47 students and 539 institutions for special and non-formal education with 42,719 students. There is a general degree college in the Islampur municipal area with 6,911 students, outside the CD Block.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\nAs per the 2011 census, in Islampur CD Block, amongst the 101 inhabited villages, 4 villages did not have a school, 59 villages had 1 or more  primary schools, 38 villages had at least 1 primary and 1 middle school and 19 villages had at least 1 middle and 1 secondary school.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011census/dchb/DCHB_A/19/1906_PART_A_DCHB_MALDAH.pdf | title = District Census Handbook, Malda, 2011, Series 20, Part XII A | work = Pages 720-21, Appendix I A:  Villages by number of Primary Schools and Appendix I B: Villages by Primary, Middle and Secondary Schools | publisher =  Directorate of Census Operations, West Bengal. | accessdate = 30 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Midday Meal Scheme|mid-day meal programme]] for rural school children was launched in 2005 in Uttar Dinajpur district. As on 30 April 2015, 602,557 children in 3,006 schools were covered under this programme.<ref>{{cite web| url =  http://uttardinajpur.nic.in/middaymeal.html |title = Cooked Mid day meal programme   |publisher= Uttar Dinajpur ditrict administration  | accessdate = 30 December 2018 }}</ref>\n\n[[Islampur College]] was established in 1973 at [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|Islampur]] (outside the CD block).<ref>{{cite web| url =  https://www.collegedekho.com/colleges/islampur-college |title = Islampur College  |publisher= College Dekho  | accessdate = 6 January 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.collegeadmission.in/IslampurCollege/Islampur_College.shtml  |title = Islampur College  |publisher=  College Admission | accessdate = 10 January 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Schools===\n*Ramganj High School at Ramganj \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school>{{cite web| url = https://www.studyapt.com/schools/secondary-schools/islampur-uttar-dinajpur-west-bengal  |title =  Secondary Schools | work=  Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|publisher=  studyapt | accessdate = 10 January 2019 }}</ref>\n*Bhadrakali High School at Gobindapur \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Darivit High School at Panditpota \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/> \n* Jagtagaon High School at Matikunda \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n* Matikunda High School at Matikunda \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Pachhu Rasia High School at Gunjaria \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Patagora High School at Agdimti-Khanti \u2013 coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Shyama Prasad S. Balika Vidyalaya at Ramganj \u2013 girls only higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Srikrishnapur High School at Matikunda \u2013 coeducationl higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n*Fazlul Haq N.S. High Madrasah at Agdimti-Khanti -  coeducational higher secondary school<ref name=school/>\n\n==Healthcare==\nIn 2013, Islampur CD Block had 1 block primary health centre and 1 [[Primary Health Centre (India)|primary health centre]], with total 14 beds and 2 doctors (excluding private bodies). It had 38 family welfare subcentres. 4,862 patients were treated indoor and 238,750 patients were treated outdoor in the hospitals, health centres and subcentres of the CD Block.<ref name=handbook2014/>\n\nIslampur subdivisional hospital  at [[Islampur, Uttar Dinajpur|Islampur]] (with 136 beds) is located outside the Islampur CD block. There is a  [[Primary Health Centre (India)|primary health centre]] at Sujali (with 4 beds).<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.wbhealth.gov.in/ | title = Health & Family Welfare Department | work= Health Statistics | publisher = Government of West Bengal  |accessdate =  12 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* {{Wikivoyage-inline|Raiganj}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|3}}\n\n{{Municipalities of West Bengal}}\n{{Uttar Dinajpur topics}}\n\n[[Category:Community development blocks in Uttar Dinajpur district]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1960-61 \u2192 1960\u201361 (14)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Islampur,_Uttar_Dinajpur_(community_development_block)"}
{"title_page": "Restrictive cardiomyopathy", "text_new": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Restrictive cardiomyopathy\n| image           = Cardiac amyloidosis very high mag.jpg\n| caption         = [[Micrograph]] of [[cardiac amyloidosis]], a cause of restrictive cardiomyopathy. [[Congo red stain]].\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| synonyms        = Obliterative cardiomyopathy, infiltrative cardiomyopathy, constrictive cardiomyopathy<ref name=Hancock>{{cite journal|last=Hancock|first=EW|title=Differential diagnosis of restrictive cardiomyopathy and constrictive pericarditis|journal=Heart|date=September 2001|volume=86|issue=3|pages=343\u20139|pmid=11514495|pmc=1729880|doi=10.1136/heart.86.3.343|doi-broken-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Restrictive cardiomyopathy''' ('''RCM''') is a form of [[cardiomyopathy]] in which the walls of the heart are rigid (but not thickened).<ref>{{DorlandsDict|two/000017373|restrictive cardiomyopathy}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Pathophysiology of heart disease : a collaborative project of medical students and faculty|date=2011|publisher=Wolters Kluwer/Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|others=Lilly, Leonard S., Harvard Medical School.|isbn=978-1605477237|edition=5th|location=Baltimore, MD|oclc=649701807}}</ref> Thus the heart is restricted from stretching and filling with blood properly. It is the least common of the three original subtypes of cardiomyopathy: [[hypertrophic cardiomyopathy|hypertrophic]], [[dilated cardiomyopathy|dilated]], and restrictive.<ref name=Hancock />\n\nIt should not be confused with [[constrictive pericarditis]], a disease which presents similarly but is very different in treatment and prognosis.<ref name=Hancock />\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nUntreated hearts with RCM often develop the following characteristics: {{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n* M or W configuration in an invasive hemodynamic pressure tracing of the RA\n* Square root sign of part of the invasive hemodynamic pressure tracing Of The LV\n* Biatrial enlargement\n* Thickened LV walls (with normal chamber size)\n* Thickened RV free wall (with normal chamber size)\n* Elevated right atrial pressure (>12mmHg), \n* Moderate [[pulmonary hypertension]], \n* Normal systolic function, \n* Poor diastolic function, typically Grade III - IV [[Diastolic heart failure]].\nThose afflicted with RCM will experience decreased exercise tolerance, fatigue, jugular venous distention, [[peripheral edema]], and [[ascites]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Arrhythmias and conduction blocks are common.\n\n==Causes==\nRCM can be caused by genetic or non-genetic factors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brodehl|first=Andreas|last2=Ferrier|first2=Raechel A.|last3=Hamilton|first3=Sara J.|last4=Greenway|first4=Steven C.|last5=Brundler|first5=Marie-Anne|last6=Yu|first6=Weiming|last7=Gibson|first7=William T.|last8=McKinnon|first8=Margaret L.|last9=McGillivray|first9=Barbara|date=March 2016|title=Mutations in FLNC are Associated with Familial Restrictive Cardiomyopathy|journal=Human Mutation|volume=37|issue=3|pages=269\u2013279|doi=10.1002/humu.22942|issn=1098-1004|pmid=26666891}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brodehl|first=Andreas|last2=Gaertner-Rommel|first2=Anna|last3=Klauke|first3=B\u00e4rbel|last4=Grewe|first4=Simon Andre|last5=Schirmer|first5=Ilona|last6=Peterschr\u00f6der|first6=Andreas|last7=Faber|first7=Lothar|last8=Vorgerd|first8=Matthias|last9=Gummert|first9=Jan|title=The novel \u03b1B-crystallin (CRYAB) mutation p.D109G causes restrictive cardiomyopathy|journal=Human Mutation|volume=38|issue=8|language=en|pages=947\u2013952|doi=10.1002/humu.23248|pmid=28493373|issn=1098-1004|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brodehl|first=Andreas|last2=Pour Hakimi|first2=Seyed Ahmad|last3=Stanasiuk|first3=Caroline|last4=Ratnavadivel|first4=Sandra|last5=Hendig|first5=Doris|last6=Gaertner|first6=Anna|last7=Gerull|first7=Brenda|last8=Gummert|first8=Jan|last9=Paluszkiewicz|first9=Lech|last10=Milting|first10=Hendrik|date=2019-11-11|title=Restrictive Cardiomyopathy is Caused by a Novel Homozygous Desmin (DES) Mutation p.Y122H Leading to a Severe Filament Assembly Defect|journal=Genes|language=en|volume=10|issue=11|pages=918|doi=10.3390/genes10110918|pmid=31718026|issn=2073-4425}}</ref> Thus it is possible to divide the causes into primary and secondary.<ref name=\"isbn0-8385-1473-12\">{{cite book|title=Current diagnosis & treatment in cardiology|author=Crawford, Michael H.|publisher=Lange Medical Books/McGraw-Hill|year=2003|isbn=978-0-8385-1473-3|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/currentdiagnosis00mich/page/188 188]|doi=|oclc=|accessdate=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/currentdiagnosis00mich/page/188}}</ref>  The common modern organization is into ''Infiltrative'', ''storage diseases'', ''non-infiltrative'', and ''endomyocardial'' etiologies:<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Muchtar|first=Eli|last2=Blauwet|first2=Lori A.|last3=Gertz|first3=Morie A.|date=2017-09-15|title=Restrictive Cardiomyopathy: Genetics, Pathogenesis, Clinical Manifestations, Diagnosis, and Therapy|journal=Circulation Research|language=en|volume=121|issue=7|pages=819\u2013837|doi=10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.117.310982|issn=0009-7330|pmid=28912185}}</ref>\n* '''Infiltrative'''\n** [[Amyloidosis]]\n** [[Sarcoidosis]]\n** [[Primary hyperoxaluria]]\n* '''Storage diseases'''\n** [[Fabry disease]]\n** [[Gaucher's disease|Gaucher disease]]\n** [[HFE hereditary haemochromatosis|Hereditary hemochromatosis]]\n** [[Glycogen storage disease]]\n** [[Mucopolysaccharidosis type I Hurler syndrome|Mucopolysaccharidosis type I (Hurler syndrome)]]\n** [[Mucopolysaccharidosis type II Hunter syndrome- mild form|Mucopolysaccharidosis type II (Hunter syndrome)]]\n** [[Niemann\u2013Pick disease|Niemann-Pick disease]]\n* '''Non-infiltrative'''\n** Idiopathic\n** [[Diabetic cardiomyopathy]]\n** [[Scleroderma]]\n** Myofibrillar myopathies\n** [[Pseudoxanthoma elasticum]]\n** Sarcomeric protein disorders\n** [[Werner syndrome|Werner's syndrome]]\n* '''Endomyocardial'''\n** [[Carcinoid|Carcinoid heart disease]]\n** [[Hypereosinophilic syndrome|Endomyocardial fibrosis]]\n** Idiopathic\n** [[Hypereosinophilic syndrome]]\n** [[Chronic eosinophilic leukemia]]\n** Drugs (serotonin, methysergide, ergotamine, mercurial agents, busulfan)\n** [[Endocardial fibroelastosis]]\n** Consequence of [[cancer]] or cancer therapy\n** Metastatic cancer\n** Drugs (anthracyclines)\n** Radiation\n\nThe most common cause of restrictive cardiomyopathy is [[amyloidosis]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Mechanism ==\n[[Cardiac rhythmicity|Rhythmicity]] and [[contractility]] of the heart may be normal, but the stiff walls of the heart chambers ([[Atrium (heart)|atria]] and [[ventricle (heart)|ventricles]]) keep them from adequately filling, reducing [[Preload (cardiology)|preload]] and [[end-diastolic volume]]. Thus, blood flow is reduced, and blood volume that would normally enter the heart is backed up in the circulatory system. In time, restrictive cardiomyopathy patients develop diastolic dysfunction and eventually [[heart failure]].\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nDiagnosis is typically made via echocardiography. Patients will demonstrate normal systolic function, diastolic dysfunction, and a restrictive filling pattern.<ref name=\":0\" /> 2-dimensional and Doppler studies are necessary to distinguish RCM from constrictive pericarditis. Cardiac MRI and transvenous [[endomyocardial biopsy]] may also be necessary in some cases.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Reduced [[QRS]] voltage on [[Ekg|EKG]] may be an indicator of amyloidosis-induced restrictive cardiomyopathy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Treatment==\nTreatment of restrictive cardiomyopathy should focus on management of causative conditions (for example, using corticosteroids if the cause is sarcoidosis), and slowing the progression of cardiomyopathy.<ref name=\":0\" /> Salt-restriction, [[diuretics]], [[angiotensin-converting-enzyme inhibitor|angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors]], and anticoagulation may be indicated for managing restrictive cardiomyopathy.<ref name=\"emedicine.medscape.com\">{{Cite journal| title = Restrictive Cardiomyopathy Treatment & Management| accessdate = 2015-06-10| date = 2014-12-18| url = http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/153062-treatment}}</ref>\n\nCalcium channel blockers are generally contraindicated due to their negative inotropic effect, particularly in cardiomyopathy caused by amyloidosis.<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1378/chest.104.2.618| pmid = 8339658| issn = 0012-3692| volume = 104| issue = 2| pages = 618\u2013620| last1 = Pollak| first1 = A| last2 = Falk| first2 = R H| title = Left ventricular systolic dysfunction precipitated by verapamil in cardiac amyloidosis.| journal = Chest| date = 1993-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/0002-9149(85)90995-6| issn = 0002-9149| volume = 55| issue = 13| pages = 1645| last1 = Gertz| first1 = Morie A.| last2 = Falk| first2 = Rodney H.| last3 = Skinner| first3 = Martha| last4 = Cohen| first4 = Alan S.| last5 = Kyle| first5 = Robert A.| title = Worsening of congestive heart failure in amyloid heart disease treated by calcium channel-blocking agents| journal = American Journal of Cardiology| date = 1985-06-01| pmid = 4003314}}</ref> Digoxin, calcium channel blocking drugs and beta-adrenergic blocking agents provide little benefit, except in the subgroup of restrictive cardiomyopathy with atrial fibrillation.<ref>{{Cite journal| issn = 1092-8464| volume = 2| issue = 5| pages = 431\u2013438| last1 = Artz| first1 = Gregory| last2 = Wynne| first2 = Joshua| title = Restrictive Cardiomyopathy| journal = Current Treatment Options in Cardiovascular Medicine| date = October 2000| pmid = 11096547| doi=10.1007/s11936-000-0038-6}}</ref> Vasodilators are also typically ineffective because systolic function is usually preserved in cases of RCM.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHeart failure resulting from restrictive cardiomyopathy will usually eventually have to be treated by [[cardiac transplantation]] or [[left ventricular assist device]].<ref name=\"emedicine.medscape.com\"/>\n\n== Epidemiology ==\nEndomyocardial fibrosis is generally limited to the tropics and sub-saharan Africa.<ref name=\":0\" /> The highest incidence of death caused by cardiac sarcoidosis is found in Japan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hulten|first=Edward|last2=Aslam|first2=Saira|last3=Osborne|first3=Michael|last4=Abbasi|first4=Siddique|last5=Bittencourt|first5=Marcio Sommer|last6=Blankstein|first6=Ron|date=February 2016|title=Cardiac sarcoidosis\u2014state of the art review|journal=Cardiovascular Diagnosis and Therapy|volume=6|issue=1|pages=50\u201363|doi=10.3978/j.issn.2223-3652.2015.12.13|issn=2223-3652|pmc=4731586|pmid=26885492}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = 11390  \n|  ICD10           = {{ICD10|I|42|5|i|30}}  \n|  ICD9            = {{ICD9|425.4}}  \n|  ICDO            =  \n|  OMIM            =  \n|  MedlinePlus     = 000189  \n|  eMedicineSubj   = med  \n|  eMedicineTopic  = 291  \n|  MeshID          = D002313 \n}}\n* [http://www.merckmanuals.com/home/heart_and_blood_vessel_disorders/cardiomyopathy/overview_of_cardiomyopathy.html Overview] at [[Merck Manual]]\n\n{{Circulatory system pathology}}\n\n[[Category:Cardiomyopathy]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox medical condition (new)\n| name            = Restrictive cardiomyopathy\n| image           = Cardiac amyloidosis very high mag.jpg\n| caption         = [[Micrograph]] of [[cardiac amyloidosis]], a cause of restrictive cardiomyopathy. [[Congo red stain]].\n| pronounce       = \n| field           = \n| synonyms        = Obliterative cardiomyopathy, infiltrative cardiomyopathy, constrictive cardiomyopathy<ref name=Hancock>{{cite journal|last=Hancock|first=EW|title=Differential diagnosis of restrictive cardiomyopathy and constrictive pericarditis|journal=Heart|date=September 2001|volume=86|issue=3|pages=343\u20139|pmid=11514495|pmc=1729880|doi=10.1136/heart.86.3.343|doi-broken-date=2019-12-10}}</ref>\n| symptoms        = \n| complications   = \n| onset           = \n| duration        = \n| types           = \n| causes          = \n| risks           = \n| diagnosis       = \n| differential    = \n| prevention      = \n| treatment       = \n| medication      = \n| prognosis       = \n| frequency       = \n| deaths          = \n}}\n'''Restrictive cardiomyopathy''' ('''RCM''') is a form of [[cardiomyopathy]] in which the walls of the heart are rigid (but not thickened).<ref>{{DorlandsDict|two/000017373|restrictive cardiomyopathy}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Pathophysiology of heart disease : a collaborative project of medical students and faculty|date=2011|publisher=Wolters Kluwer/Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|others=Lilly, Leonard S., Harvard Medical School.|isbn=978-1605477237|edition=5th|location=Baltimore, MD|oclc=649701807}}</ref> Thus the heart is restricted from stretching and filling with blood properly. It is the least common of the three original subtypes of cardiomyopathy: [[hypertrophic cardiomyopathy|hypertrophic]], [[dilated cardiomyopathy|dilated]], and restrictive.<ref name=Hancock />\n\nIt should not be confused with [[constrictive pericarditis]], a disease which presents similarly but is very different in treatment and prognosis.<ref name=Hancock />\n\n==Signs and symptoms==\nUntreated hearts with RCM often develop the following characteristics: {{citation needed|date=May 2019}}\n* M or W configuration in an invasive hemodynamic pressure tracing of the RA\n* Square root sign of part of the invasive hemodynamic pressure tracing Of The LV\n* Biatrial enlargement\n* Thickened LV walls (with normal chamber size)\n* Thickened RV free wall (with normal chamber size)\n* Elevated right atrial pressure (>12mmHg), \n* Moderate [[pulmonary hypertension]], \n* Normal systolic function, \n* Poor diastolic function, typically Grade III - IV [[Diastolic heart failure]].\nThose afflicted with RCM will experience decreased exercise tolerance, fatigue, jugular venous distention, [[peripheral edema]], and [[ascites]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Arrhythmias and conduction blocks are common.\n\n==Causes==\nRCM can be caused by genetic or non-genetic factors.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brodehl|first=Andreas|last2=Ferrier|first2=Raechel A.|last3=Hamilton|first3=Sara J.|last4=Greenway|first4=Steven C.|last5=Brundler|first5=Marie-Anne|last6=Yu|first6=Weiming|last7=Gibson|first7=William T.|last8=McKinnon|first8=Margaret L.|last9=McGillivray|first9=Barbara|date=March 2016|title=Mutations in FLNC are Associated with Familial Restrictive Cardiomyopathy|journal=Human Mutation|volume=37|issue=3|pages=269\u2013279|doi=10.1002/humu.22942|issn=1098-1004|pmid=26666891}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brodehl|first=Andreas|last2=Gaertner-Rommel|first2=Anna|last3=Klauke|first3=B\u00e4rbel|last4=Grewe|first4=Simon Andre|last5=Schirmer|first5=Ilona|last6=Peterschr\u00f6der|first6=Andreas|last7=Faber|first7=Lothar|last8=Vorgerd|first8=Matthias|last9=Gummert|first9=Jan|title=The novel \u03b1B-crystallin (CRYAB) mutation p.D109G causes restrictive cardiomyopathy|journal=Human Mutation|volume=38|issue=8|language=en|pages=947\u2013952|doi=10.1002/humu.23248|pmid=28493373|issn=1098-1004|year=2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brodehl|first=Andreas|last2=Pour Hakimi|first2=Seyed Ahmad|last3=Stanasiuk|first3=Caroline|last4=Ratnavadivel|first4=Sandra|last5=Hendig|first5=Doris|last6=Gaertner|first6=Anna|last7=Gerull|first7=Brenda|last8=Gummert|first8=Jan|last9=Paluszkiewicz|first9=Lech|last10=Milting|first10=Hendrik|date=2019-11-11|title=Restrictive Cardiomyopathy is Caused by a Novel Homozygous Desmin (DES) Mutation p.Y122H Leading to a Severe Filament Assembly Defect|journal=Genes|language=en|volume=10|issue=11|pages=918|doi=10.3390/genes10110918|pmid=31718026|issn=2073-4425}}</ref> Thus it is possible to divide the causes into primary and secondary.<ref name=\"isbn0-8385-1473-12\">{{cite book|title=Current diagnosis & treatment in cardiology|author=Crawford, Michael H.|publisher=Lange Medical Books/McGraw-Hill|year=2003|isbn=978-0-8385-1473-3|location=New York|pages=[https://archive.org/details/currentdiagnosis00mich/page/188 188]|doi=|oclc=|accessdate=|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/currentdiagnosis00mich/page/188}}</ref>  The common modern organization is into ''Infiltrative'', ''storage diseases'', ''non-infiltrative'', and ''endomyocardial'' etiologies:<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Muchtar|first=Eli|last2=Blauwet|first2=Lori A.|last3=Gertz|first3=Morie A.|date=2017-09-15|title=Restrictive Cardiomyopathy: Genetics, Pathogenesis, Clinical Manifestations, Diagnosis, and Therapy|journal=Circulation Research|language=en|volume=121|issue=7|pages=819\u2013837|doi=10.1161/CIRCRESAHA.117.310982|issn=0009-7330|pmid=28912185}}</ref>\n* '''Infiltrative'''\n** [[Amyloidosis]]\n** [[Sarcoidosis]]\n** [[Primary hyperoxaluria]]\n* '''Storage diseases'''\n** [[Fabry disease]]\n** [[Gaucher's disease|Gaucher disease]]\n** [[HFE hereditary haemochromatosis|Hereditary hemochromatosis]]\n** [[Glycogen storage disease]]\n** [[Mucopolysaccharidosis type I Hurler syndrome|Mucopolysaccharidosis type I (Hurler syndrome)]]\n** [[Mucopolysaccharidosis type II Hunter syndrome- mild form|Mucopolysaccharidosis type II (Hunter syndrome)]]\n** [[Niemann\u2013Pick disease|Niemann-Pick disease]]\n* '''Non-infiltrative'''\n** Idiopathic\n** [[Diabetic cardiomyopathy]]\n** [[Scleroderma]]\n** Myofibrillar myopathies\n** [[Pseudoxanthoma elasticum]]\n** Sarcomeric protein disorders\n** [[Werner syndrome|Werner\u2019s syndrome]]\n* '''Endomyocardial'''\n** [[Carcinoid|Carcinoid heart disease]]\n** [[Hypereosinophilic syndrome|Endomyocardial fibrosis]]\n** Idiopathic\n** [[Hypereosinophilic syndrome]]\n** [[Chronic eosinophilic leukemia]]\n** Drugs (serotonin, methysergide, ergotamine, mercurial agents, busulfan)\n** [[Endocardial fibroelastosis]]\n** Consequence of [[cancer]] or cancer therapy\n** Metastatic cancer\n** Drugs (anthracyclines)\n** Radiation\n\nThe most common cause of restrictive cardiomyopathy is [[amyloidosis]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Mechanism ==\n[[Cardiac rhythmicity|Rhythmicity]] and [[contractility]] of the heart may be normal, but the stiff walls of the heart chambers ([[Atrium (heart)|atria]] and [[ventricle (heart)|ventricles]]) keep them from adequately filling, reducing [[Preload (cardiology)|preload]] and [[end-diastolic volume]]. Thus, blood flow is reduced, and blood volume that would normally enter the heart is backed up in the circulatory system. In time, restrictive cardiomyopathy patients develop diastolic dysfunction and eventually [[heart failure]].\n\n== Diagnosis ==\nDiagnosis is typically made via echocardiography. Patients will demonstrate normal systolic function, diastolic dysfunction, and a restrictive filling pattern.<ref name=\":0\" /> 2-dimensional and Doppler studies are necessary to distinguish RCM from constrictive pericarditis. Cardiac MRI and transvenous [[endomyocardial biopsy]] may also be necessary in some cases.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> Reduced [[QRS]] voltage on [[Ekg|EKG]] may be an indicator of amyloidosis-induced restrictive cardiomyopathy.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Treatment==\nTreatment of restrictive cardiomyopathy should focus on management of causative conditions (for example, using corticosteroids if the cause is sarcoidosis), and slowing the progression of cardiomyopathy.<ref name=\":0\" /> Salt-restriction, [[diuretics]], [[angiotensin-converting-enzyme inhibitor|angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors]], and anticoagulation may be indicated for managing restrictive cardiomyopathy.<ref name=\"emedicine.medscape.com\">{{Cite journal| title = Restrictive Cardiomyopathy Treatment & Management| accessdate = 2015-06-10| date = 2014-12-18| url = http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/153062-treatment}}</ref>\n\nCalcium channel blockers are generally contraindicated due to their negative inotropic effect, particularly in cardiomyopathy caused by amyloidosis.<ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1378/chest.104.2.618| pmid = 8339658| issn = 0012-3692| volume = 104| issue = 2| pages = 618\u2013620| last1 = Pollak| first1 = A| last2 = Falk| first2 = R H| title = Left ventricular systolic dysfunction precipitated by verapamil in cardiac amyloidosis.| journal = Chest| date = 1993-08-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal| doi = 10.1016/0002-9149(85)90995-6| issn = 0002-9149| volume = 55| issue = 13| pages = 1645| last1 = Gertz| first1 = Morie A.| last2 = Falk| first2 = Rodney H.| last3 = Skinner| first3 = Martha| last4 = Cohen| first4 = Alan S.| last5 = Kyle| first5 = Robert A.| title = Worsening of congestive heart failure in amyloid heart disease treated by calcium channel-blocking agents| journal = American Journal of Cardiology| date = 1985-06-01| pmid = 4003314}}</ref> Digoxin, calcium channel blocking drugs and beta-adrenergic blocking agents provide little benefit, except in the subgroup of restrictive cardiomyopathy with atrial fibrillation.<ref>{{Cite journal| issn = 1092-8464| volume = 2| issue = 5| pages = 431\u2013438| last1 = Artz| first1 = Gregory| last2 = Wynne| first2 = Joshua| title = Restrictive Cardiomyopathy| journal = Current Treatment Options in Cardiovascular Medicine| date = October 2000| pmid = 11096547| doi=10.1007/s11936-000-0038-6}}</ref> Vasodilators are also typically ineffective because systolic function is usually preserved in cases of RCM.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nHeart failure resulting from restrictive cardiomyopathy will usually eventually have to be treated by [[cardiac transplantation]] or [[left ventricular assist device]].<ref name=\"emedicine.medscape.com\"/>\n\n== Epidemiology ==\nEndomyocardial fibrosis is generally limited to the tropics and sub-saharan Africa.<ref name=\":0\" /> The highest incidence of death caused by cardiac sarcoidosis is found in Japan.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Hulten|first=Edward|last2=Aslam|first2=Saira|last3=Osborne|first3=Michael|last4=Abbasi|first4=Siddique|last5=Bittencourt|first5=Marcio Sommer|last6=Blankstein|first6=Ron|date=February 2016|title=Cardiac sarcoidosis\u2014state of the art review|journal=Cardiovascular Diagnosis and Therapy|volume=6|issue=1|pages=50\u201363|doi=10.3978/j.issn.2223-3652.2015.12.13|issn=2223-3652|pmc=4731586|pmid=26885492}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Medical resources\n|  DiseasesDB      = 11390  \n|  ICD10           = {{ICD10|I|42|5|i|30}}  \n|  ICD9            = {{ICD9|425.4}}  \n|  ICDO            =  \n|  OMIM            =  \n|  MedlinePlus     = 000189  \n|  eMedicineSubj   = med  \n|  eMedicineTopic  = 291  \n|  MeshID          = D002313 \n}}\n* [http://www.merckmanuals.com/home/heart_and_blood_vessel_disorders/cardiomyopathy/overview_of_cardiomyopathy.html Overview] at [[Merck Manual]]\n\n{{Circulatory system pathology}}\n\n[[Category:Cardiomyopathy]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCauses:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Restrictive_cardiomyopathy"}
{"title_page": "Big Hit Entertainment", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Big Hit Entertainment\n| native_name = (\uc8fc) \ube45\ud788\ud2b8 \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\n| native_name_lang = ko\n| romanized_name = ''Big hiteu enteoteinmeonteu''\n| trading_name = \n| logo = Big Hit Entertainment Logo black.svg\n| logo_caption = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| traded_as = \n| founder = [[Bang Si-hyuk]]\n| area_served = \n| key_people = {{ubl|Bang Si-hyuk (co-CEO)|Lenzo Yoon (co-CEO)}}\n| industry = [[Entertainment]]\n| genre = {{ubl|[[Dance music|Dance]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Hip hop music|Hip-Hop]]}}\n| products = \n| services = {{Unbulleted list|Music production|Licensing|Record distribution}}\n| revenue = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{increase}} US $494.6 million (2019)}}<ref name=\"revenue2019\">{{cite news|title=BTS Label Big Hit Entertainment Nearly Doubles Revenue From Previous Year, Adds $15 Million In Operating Profit|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2020/02/05/bts-label-big-hit-entertainment-nearly-doubles-revenue-from-previous-year-adds-15-million-in-operating-profit/|work=Forbes|first=Jeff|last=Benjamin|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| net_income = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{increase}} US $82.4 million (2019)}}<ref name=\"revenue2019\" />\n| owner =\n* Bang Si-hyuk (50.88%)<ref>{{cite news|title=\uc591\ud604\uc11d \ub118\uc740 \ubc15\uc9c4\uc601\u2026 BTS \ub300\ubc15\uc5d0 \ubc29\uc2dc\ud601 1\uc704|url=http://news.hankyung.com/article/2018032749871|work=Hankyung|first=Man-soo|last=Choi|language=ko|date=March 27, 2018|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Netmarble Games]] (25.71%) \n* [[STIC Investments]] (12%)\n| num_employees = Approx. 600 (As of January 2020)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bighitcorp.com/eng/|title=Big Hit Entertainment <sub>''(in \"Who We Are\" section)''</sub>}}</ref>\n| subsid = [[Source Music]] (2019-present)\n| footnotes = \n| homepage = {{URL|bighitcorp.com}}\n| foundation = {{Start date|2005|2|1}}\n| location_city = [[Seoul]] Gangnam-gu, 5 30-gil, Hakdong-ro, Floor Yangjin Plaza 5F\n| location_country = [[South Korea]]\n| dissolved = \n}}\n \n'''Big Hit Entertainment, Co.''' ({{korean|hangul=\ube45\ud788\ud2b8\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8}}) is a South Korean entertainment company established in 2005 by [[Bang Si-hyuk]]. It currently manages soloist [[Lee Hyun]] and idol groups [[BTS (band)|BTS]] and [[TXT (band)|TXT]]. Since July 2019, Big Hit has one subsidiary label, [[Source Music]], home to idol group [[GFriend]].\n\n==History==\nBig Hit Entertainment was founded on February 1, 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibighit.com/introduction/sub_introduction1.asp|title=Introduction|publisher=BigHit Entertainment|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101193030/http://www.ibighit.com/introduction/sub_introduction1.asp|archive-date=November 1, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=July 24, 2015}}</ref> and signed the vocal trio [[8Eight]], consisting of [[Lee Hyun]], Baek Chan, and Joo Hee, in 2007.\n\nIn 2010, Big Hit Entertainment and [[JYP Entertainment]] signed a joint management contract over the boy group [[2AM (band)|2AM]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/63193/2am-changes-agencies|title=KPOP NEWS - 2AM\u2019s Jo Kwon, Im Seulong, and Jung Jin Woon Return to JYP Entertainment|work=Mwave|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312112024/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/63193/2am-changes-agencies|archive-date=March 12, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> That year, Bang Si-hyuk launched nationwide auditions and signed [[RM (rapper)|RM]] as the first member of [[BTS (band)|BTS]], who was then followed by the other members of the group.<ref>{{cite journal|date=July 22, 2013|title=[INTERVIEW] Bangtan Boys|url=http://www.cuvismmag.com/b/interview/2922|journal=Cuvism Magazine|language=ko|access-date=July 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606161844/http://cuvismmag.com/b/interview/2922|archive-date=June 6, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> BTS made their debut under Big Hit on 13 June,2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/38336/bts-releases-debut-video|title=KPOP NEWS - [Video] BTS Asks about Your Dreams in \u2018No More Dream\u2019 MV|work=Mwave|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the company signed [[Lim Jeong-hee]],<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/95932/big-hit-reveals-lim-jeong-hees-contract-ended-in-may|title=KPOP NEWS - Big Hit Reveals Lim Jeong Hee\u2032s Contract Ended in May|work=Mwave|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230062103/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/95932/big-hit-reveals-lim-jeong-hees-contract-ended-in-may|archive-date=December 30, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> and the girl group [[GLAM (band)|GLAM]] was formed as a collaboration with Source Music. They were active until 2014, when they disbanded due to a controversy over one of the members, Kim Da-hee, who was sentenced to prison following accusations of blackmailing actor [[Lee Byung-hun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/utype.htm?id=201501160100179660010908&ServiceDate=20150115|script-title=ko:\uae00\ub7a8, \uacb0\uad6d 3\ub144 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \ud574\uccb4\u2026'\uc774\ubcd1\ud5cc \ud611\ubc15\u5973' \ub2e4\ud76c-\uc774\uc9c0\uc5f0 \uc2e4\ud615 \uc120\uace0 : \uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\uc870\uc120|work=Sports Chosun|language=ko|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/utype.htm?id=201409030100028830001520&ServiceDate=20140902|script-title=ko:\uae00\ub7a8 \ub2e4\ud76c, \ubaa8\ub378 \uce5c\uad6c\uc640 \uc74c\ub2f4\ud328\uc124 \uc601\uc0c1 \uc720\ud3ec \ud611\ubc15 \"\uc138\uacc4\uc801 \uc2a4\ud0c0\ub77c \uac70\uc561 \uc694\uad6c\" \uc774\ubcd1\ud5cc \uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5\uc740? : \uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\uc870\uc120|work=Sports Chosun|language=ko|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201502261617272907645_2|title=Lee Byung-hun repeats apology upon returning home|work=The Korea Herald|access-date=November 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of the joint contract between Big Hit and JYP Entertainment in April 2014, three of the 2AM members returned to JYP, while [[Lee Chang-min (singer)|Lee Chang-min]] stayed with Big Hit in order to continue with his solo career and as part of the duo [[Homme (band)|Homme]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The year also saw the disbandment of 8Eight after Baek Chan and Joo Hee's contracts with Big Hit ended.\n\nIn May 2015, [[Signal Entertainment Group]], a [[KOSDAQ]]-listed company specializing in artist management and television production, acquired Big Hit through a KR\u20a96 billion [[convertible bond]],<ref name=\"edaily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edaily.co.kr/news/NewsRead.edy?SCD=JB31&newsid=03450566609368920&DCD=A10103&OutLnkChk=Y|script-title=ko:\uc528\uadf8\ub110\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\uadf8\ub8f9 \"\ube45\ud788\ud2b8\uc5d4\ud130 CB 60\uc5b5 \uc778\uc218\"|work=eDaily|language=ko|trans-title=Signal Entertainment Group acquires Big Hit Ent for 60 billion \"through CB\"|access-date=February 4, 2016}}</ref> and Lim Jeong-hee parted ways with the agency, following the expiration of her three-year contract.<ref name=\":1\" /> In early 2017, Big Hit ended their stake relationship with Signal Entertainment Group. Big Hit issued a 6 billion won convertible bond Signal Entertainment Group in 2015. After a year, Signal Entertainment Group made a full settlement of the bonds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thebell.co.kr/m/newsview.asp?svccode=00&newskey=201702090100018900001148|script-title=ko:\ube45\ud788\ud2b8\uc5d4\ud130, \uc601\uc5c5\uc774\uc775 100\uc5b5 \ub3cc\ud30c\u2026VC '\ud750\ubb47'|work=The Bell|language=ko|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/099830.KQ/key-developments/article/3449988|title=Signal Entertainment Group to sell entire shares of entertainment firm for 6.2 bln won|date=October 6, 2016|work=[[Reuters]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323085540/https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/099830.KQ/key-developments/article/3449988|archive-date=March 23, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Homme disbanded after member Changmin's contract came to an end. He left the company to start his own agency, while Lee Hyun continued on as a solo artist.<ref name=\"Lee Hyun now solo\">{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=311&aid=0000818920|script-title=ko:[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] \uc774\ucc3d\ubbfc, \ube45\ud788\ud2b8\uc640 \uc804\uc18d\uacc4\uc57d \ub9cc\ub8cc \"1\uc778 \uae30\ud68d\uc0ac \uc124\ub9bd\"|date=February 1, 2018|work=Xsports News|language=ko|trans-title=Lee Changmin's contract with Bighit Entertainment expires, \"will start his own agency\"|access-date=August 3, 2019|via=[[Naver]]}}</ref> Later that year in October, Big Hit Entertainment announced that BTS had renewed and extended their contract with them for seven more years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2018/10/17/bts-extend-contracts-with-big-hit-entertainment-until-2026/|title=BTS Extend Contracts With Big Hit Entertainment Until 2026|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=October 17, 2018|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, male group [[TXT (band)|Tomorrow X Together]] (TXT) made their debut under Big Hit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/caitlinkelley/2019/02/06/bts-bighit-tomorrow-x-together-txt-debut/|title=BTS's Label Reveals TOMORROW X TOGETHER Will Debut March 4|last=Kelley|first=Caitlin|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> Former [[Chief business officer|CBO]] Lenzo Yoon was also appointed co-CEO with Bang Si-hyuk,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2019/03/07/big-hit-entertainment-appoints-new-co-ceo-following-rise-of-bts-launch-of-txt/#4189f8e62f79|title=Big Hit Entertainment Appoints New Co-CEO Following Rise Of BTS, Launch Of TXT|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=March 7, 2019|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> focusing on the business components of the company while Bang will focus on creative production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=108&aid=0002765749|script-title=ko:\ube45\ud788\ud2b8 '\ubc29\ud0c4 \uc131\uc7a5 \uc8fc\uc5ed' \uc724\uc11d\uc900 \uacf5\ub3d9 \ub300\ud45c\uc774\uc0ac \uc120\uc784|last=Lee|first=Jung-ho|date=March 6, 2019|work=Star News|language=ko|trans-title=Big Hit 'Ballistic Growth Leader' Yoon Seok-jun appointed as co-CEO|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306111759/https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=108&aid=0002765749|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=August 3, 2019|via=[[Naver]]}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the agency acquired [[Source Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/caitlinkelley/2019/07/28/btss-label-big-hit-entertainment-acquired-source-music/|title=Big Hit Entertainment, BTS\u2019s Label, Acquires Source Music|last=Kelley|first=Caitlin|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Company value and investments==\nIn 2007, Big Hit Entertainment was near bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-17/mogul-behind-world-s-most-tweeted-about-boy-band-considers-ipo|title=Mogul Behind K-Pop Boy Band BTS Considers IPO}}</ref> Due to the success of early groups [[8Eight]] and [[2AM (band)|2AM]], Bang was able to keep the company afloat{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} and later created the group [[BTS (band)|BTS]] in 2013. Varying reports consider the current total value of the company at roughly 1T KRW (~891.5M USD).<ref name=\"theinvestor.co.kr\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20181011000694|title=STIC Investments invests W104b in Big Hit|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en}}</ref> Many consider the company's profit in both the Western and Eastern markets, Big Hit's relatively lenient policies towards their idols' creativity, and innovative music styles to be a cornerstone of the label's success.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nBig Hit Entertainment currently operates as a private company. Bang Si-hyuk remains the largest shareholder of Big Hit  stock. In March 2017, the Korean mobile gaming company [[Netmarble Games|Netmarble]] acquired the second largest percentage of the company, paying a reported 201.4B KRW (191.8M USD) for 25.71%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajudaily.com/view/20180404164806895|title=Game maker becomes second largest shareholder of BTS' agency}}</ref> The CEO of Netmarble, Bang Joon-Hyuk, and Bang Si-hyuk are cousins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3046607|title=Cousins unite as Netmarble buys stake in Bit Hit|last=Ha|first=Sun-young|date=April 7, 2018|work=Korea JoongAng Daily|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407131610/http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3046607|archive-date=April 7, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Big Hit publicized its earnings for the first time, reporting revenue at 92.4B KRW (~82M USD).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20180326000769|title=Expectations high for BTS-backed Big Hit Entertainment\u2019s IPO|last=Lee|first=Ji-Yoo|date=March 26, 2018|work=The Investor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107104354/http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20180326000769|archive-date=November 7, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2019-08-03|via=The Korea Herald}}</ref> If entered into an [[Initial public offering|IPO]], the company itself could reach a value of up to 700B KRW (~624M USD), potentially ousting the typically powerful \"Big 3\" companies [[SM Entertainment]], [[JYP Entertainment]], and [[YG Entertainment]]. This would make CEO Bang the richest in the South Korean entertainment business due to his large shareholding position, and leave him with personal ownership value of roughly 350B KRW (~314M USD).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hankyung.com/finance/article/2018032749871|script-title=ko:\uc591\ud604\uc11d \ub118\uc740 \ubc15\uc9c4\uc601\u2026 BTS \ub300\ubc15\uc5d0 \ubc29\uc2dc\ud601 1\uc704|last=Choi|first=Man-soo|date=March 27, 2018|work=Hankyung|language=ko|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729143619/https://www.hankyung.com/finance/article/2018032749871|archive-date=July 29, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Big Hit Entertainment and [[CJ E&M]], another Korean entertainment agency, released information stating plans to create a joint company. Filed under the name Belift, the company will reportedly be split 52% to CJ E&M, and 48% to Big Hit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/business/2018/07/31/0501000000AEN20180731008500315.html|title=BTS' management agency teams up with CJ affiliate to launch entertainment firm|last=\ubc15\ubcf4\ub78c|date=July 31, 2018|work=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> The group is set to debut in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/03/12/2019031201432.html|title=Entertainment Giants Team up to Manufacture 'Next BTS'|last=Kim|first=Bong-kee|date=March 12, 2019|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|access-date=March 12, 2019}}</ref> CJ E&M's recent foray into idol production television shows such as [[Produce 101]] and Big Hit's growing global auditions are likely to be the venture philosophy of the new company.\n\nIn October 2018, private investment firm [[STIC Investments]] received a reported 12% share of Big Hit Entertainment, an investment of roughly 104B KRW (~93M USD).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paxnet.co.kr/news/mainView?vNewsSetId=5617&articleId=2018101111304401641&wlog_nsise=popularnews|title=\uc2a4\ud2f1\uc778\ubca0\uc2a4\ud2b8, BTS\uc5d0 1040\uc5b5 \ubca0\ud305|date=2018-11-10|website=www.paxnet.co.kr|language=ko|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803094321/http://www.paxnet.co.kr/news/mainView?vNewsSetId=5617&articleId=2018101111304401641&wlog_nsise=popularnews|archive-date=2019-08-03|url-status=live|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> According to the Investor, Big Hit's posted revenue and operating profit of 92.4B (~82M USD) and 32.5B KRW (~29M USD) is expected to return more than double at 230B (~205M USD) and 83B KRW (~74M USD) by the end of 2018.<ref name=\"theinvestor.co.kr\"/> Big Hit was voted best investment company of the year for 2018 at the Korea VC Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&oid=008&aid=0004143145&sid1=001|script-title=ko:\ud55c\uad6d\ubca4\ucc98\ud22c\uc790, \u2018Korea VC Awards 2018\u2019 \uac1c\ucd5c|last=Lee|first=Sang-yeon|date=December 6, 2018|work=Money Today|language=ko|access-date=August 3, 2019|via=[[Naver]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019 the company announced their 2018 audit report. They experienced a 132% increase in sales compared to 2017 making approximately 214.2B KRW, or about US$189.38 million. They had a 97% percent increase in operating profit for the year making 64.1B KRW (US$56.72 million) and a 105% percent increase in net profit making 50.2B KRW (US$44.41 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bts/8503273/bts-label-big-hit-entertainment-record-results-2018|title=BTS Helps Label Big Hit Entertainment to Record Result In 2018|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=March 20, 2019|work=Billboard|access-date=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Subsidiaries and affiliates==\n* beNX<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20190702000587&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=BTS' management company to move into new building|date=July 2, 2019|publisher=The Korea Herald|language=en|accessdate=}}</ref>\n* BELIFT (co-managed by [[CJ E&M]])\n* Superb<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/tech/8527708/big-hit-superb-gaming-company-bts|title=BTS' Agency Big Hit Acquires Superb Gaming Company|date=August 19, 2019|publisher=Billboard|language=en|accessdate=}}</ref>\n* [[Source Music]]\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIt was revealed the company donated 30 million won, roughly US$25,500, to the [[Sinking of MV Sewol|Sewol Disaster]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5]\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8, \uc138\uc6d4\ud638 \ucc38\uc0ac 416\uac00\uc871\ud611\uc758\ud68c\uc5d0 1\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uae30\ubd80 |url=https://entertain.naver.com/ranking/read?oid=112&aid=0002886804|website=Naver|accessdate=May 23, 2019|language=Korean|date=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Artists==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Groups===\n* [[8Eight]]\n* [[BTS (band)|BTS]]\n* [[TXT (band)|TXT]]\n\n===Soloists===\n* [[Lee Hyun]] \n* [[RM (rapper)|RM]]\n* [[Suga (rapper)|Agust D]] \n* [[J-Hope]]\n\n===Actors===\n* [[V (singer)|Kim Tae-hyung]]\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Producers===\n* [[Bang Si-hyuk|\"Hitman\" Bang]]\n* Slow Rabbit<ref>{{cite web|last1=Herman|first1=Tamar|title=7 Factors That Helped Propel BTS To No. 1 On The Billboard 200|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2018/05/31/7-factors-that-helped-propel-bts-to-no-1-on-the-billboard-200/#6dc3059c12a4|website=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=March 11, 2019|date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* Adora<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=\"Si\u00eau t\u00e2n binh\" TXT: C\u00f3 l\u00e0m n\u00ean kh\u00e1c bi\u1ec7t hay ch\u1ec9 \"g\u00e2y b\u00e3o\" nh\u1edd h\u00e0o quang c\u1ee7a BTS?|url=http://kenh14.vn/sieu-tan-binh-txt-co-lam-nen-khac-biet-hay-chi-gay-bao-nho-hao-quang-cua-bts-20190305102003386.chn|website=kenh14|accessdate=March 11, 2019|language=Vietnamese|date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n* Pdogg<ref name =\":5\">{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Arin|title=BTS' team sweeps four awards at 2018 MAMA in Seoul|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/life/2018/12/11/bts-team-sweeps-four-awards-at-2018-mama-in-seoul.html|website=[[The Jakarta Post]]|accessdate=March 11, 2019|date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n* Supreme Boi<ref name=\":4\"/>\n* Docskim\n* Runch Randa\n* Hissnoise\n\n===Choreographers===\n* Son Sung-deuk<ref name =\":5\"/>\n* Kim Su-bin\n* David DH. Park\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Former artists==\n* [[K.Will]] (2006\u20132007)\n* [[2AM (band)|2AM]] (2010\u20132014, co-managed by [[JYP Entertainment]])\n** Baek Chan (2007-2014)\n** Joo Hee (2007-2014)\n* [[Glam (group)|Glam]] (2012\u20132015, co-managed by Source Music) \n* [[Lim Jeong-hee]] (2012\u20132015)\n* [[Homme (band)|Homme]] (2010\u20132018)\n** [[Lee Chang-min (singer)|Changmin]] (2010\u20132018)<ref name=\"Lee Hyun now solo\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Big Hit Entertainment discography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.bighitcorp.com/eng/}}\n\n{{Big Hit Entertainment}}\n{{K-pop}}\n\n[[Category:Signal Entertainment Group]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Labels distributed by Kakao M]]\n[[Category:Pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2005]]\n[[Category:South Korean record labels]]\n[[Category:Talent agencies of South Korea]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Big Hit Entertainment\n| native_name = (\uc8fc) \ube45\ud788\ud2b8 \uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\n| native_name_lang = ko\n| romanized_name = ''Big hiteu enteoteinmeonteu''\n| trading_name = \n| logo = Big Hit Entertainment Logo black.svg\n| logo_caption = \n| type = [[Privately held company|Private]]\n| traded_as = \n| founder = [[Bang Si-hyuk]]\n| area_served = \n| key_people = {{ubl|Bang Si-hyuk (co-CEO)|Lenzo Yoon (co-CEO)}}\n| industry = [[Entertainment]]\n| genre = {{ubl|[[Dance music|Dance]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Hip hop music|Hip-Hop]]}}\n| products = \n| services = {{Unbulleted list|Music production|Licensing|Record distribution}}\n| revenue = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{increase}} US $494.6 million (2019)}}<ref name=\"revenue2019\">{{cite news|title=BTS Label Big Hit Entertainment Nearly Doubles Revenue From Previous Year, Adds $15 Million In Operating Profit|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jeffbenjamin/2020/02/05/bts-label-big-hit-entertainment-nearly-doubles-revenue-from-previous-year-adds-15-million-in-operating-profit/|work=Forbes|first=Jeff|last=Benjamin|date=February 5, 2020|accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n| net_income = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{increase}} US $82.4 million (2019)}}<ref name=\"revenue2019\" />\n| owner =\n* Bang Si-hyuk (50.88%)<ref>{{cite news|title=\uc591\ud604\uc11d \ub118\uc740 \ubc15\uc9c4\uc601\u2026 BTS \ub300\ubc15\uc5d0 \ubc29\uc2dc\ud601 1\uc704|url=http://news.hankyung.com/article/2018032749871|work=Hankyung|first=Man-soo|last=Choi|language=ko|date=March 27, 2018|accessdate=May 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Netmarble Games]] (25.71%) \n* [[STIC Investments]] (12%)\n| num_employees = Approx. 600 (As of January 2020)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bighitcorp.com/eng/|title=Big Hit Entertainment <sub>''(in \"Who We Are\" section)''</sub>}}</ref>\n| subsid = [[Source Music]] (2019-present)\n| footnotes = \n| homepage = {{URL|bighitcorp.com}}\n| foundation = {{Start date|2005|2|1}}\n| location_city = [[Seoul]] Gangnam-gu, 5 30-gil, Hakdong-ro, Floor Yangjin Plaza 5F\n| location_country = [[South Korea]]\n| dissolved = \n}}\n \n'''Big Hit Entertainment, Co.''' ({{korean|hangul=\ube45\ud788\ud2b8\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8}}) is a South Korean entertainment company established in 2005 by [[Bang Si-hyuk]]. It currently manages soloist [[Lee Hyun]] and idol groups [[BTS (band)|BTS]] and [[TXT (band)|TXT]]. Since July 2019, Big Hit has one subsidiary label, [[Source Music]], home to idol group [[GFriend]].\n\n==History==\nBig Hit Entertainment was founded on February 1, 2005,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibighit.com/introduction/sub_introduction1.asp|title=Introduction|publisher=BigHit Entertainment|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171101193030/http://www.ibighit.com/introduction/sub_introduction1.asp|archive-date=November 1, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=July 24, 2015}}</ref> and signed the vocal trio [[8Eight]], consisting of [[Lee Hyun]], Baek Chan, and Joo Hee, in 2007.\n\nIn 2010, Big Hit Entertainment and [[JYP Entertainment]] signed a joint management contract over the boy group [[2AM (band)|2AM]].<ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/63193/2am-changes-agencies|title=KPOP NEWS - 2AM\u2019s Jo Kwon, Im Seulong, and Jung Jin Woon Return to JYP Entertainment|work=Mwave|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312112024/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/63193/2am-changes-agencies|archive-date=March 12, 2016|url-status=dead|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> That year, Bang Si-hyuk launched nationwide auditions and signed [[RM (rapper)|RM]] as the first member of [[BTS (band)|BTS]], who was then followed by the other members of the group.<ref>{{cite journal|date=July 22, 2013|title=[INTERVIEW] Bangtan Boys|url=http://www.cuvismmag.com/b/interview/2922|journal=Cuvism Magazine|language=ko|access-date=July 18, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150606161844/http://cuvismmag.com/b/interview/2922|archive-date=June 6, 2015|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref> BTS made their debut under Big Hit on 13 June,2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/38336/bts-releases-debut-video|title=KPOP NEWS - [Video] BTS Asks about Your Dreams in \u2018No More Dream\u2019 MV|work=Mwave|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, the company signed [[Lim Jeong-hee]],<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/95932/big-hit-reveals-lim-jeong-hees-contract-ended-in-may|title=KPOP NEWS - Big Hit Reveals Lim Jeong Hee\u2032s Contract Ended in May|work=Mwave|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230062103/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/95932/big-hit-reveals-lim-jeong-hees-contract-ended-in-may|archive-date=December 30, 2015|url-status=dead|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref> and the girl group [[GLAM (band)|GLAM]] was formed as a collaboration with Source Music. They were active until 2014, when they disbanded due to a controversy over one of the members, Kim Da-hee, who was sentenced to prison following accusations of blackmailing actor [[Lee Byung-hun]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/utype.htm?id=201501160100179660010908&ServiceDate=20150115|script-title=ko:\uae00\ub7a8, \uacb0\uad6d 3\ub144 \ub9cc\uc5d0 \ud574\uccb4\u2026'\uc774\ubcd1\ud5cc \ud611\ubc15\u5973' \ub2e4\ud76c-\uc774\uc9c0\uc5f0 \uc2e4\ud615 \uc120\uace0 : \uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\uc870\uc120|work=Sports Chosun|language=ko|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/utype.htm?id=201409030100028830001520&ServiceDate=20140902|script-title=ko:\uae00\ub7a8 \ub2e4\ud76c, \ubaa8\ub378 \uce5c\uad6c\uc640 \uc74c\ub2f4\ud328\uc124 \uc601\uc0c1 \uc720\ud3ec \ud611\ubc15 \"\uc138\uacc4\uc801 \uc2a4\ud0c0\ub77c \uac70\uc561 \uc694\uad6c\" \uc774\ubcd1\ud5cc \uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5\uc740? : \uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\uc870\uc120|work=Sports Chosun|language=ko|access-date=June 30, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201502261617272907645_2|title=Lee Byung-hun repeats apology upon returning home|work=The Korea Herald|access-date=November 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the end of the joint contract between Big Hit and JYP Entertainment in April 2014, three of the 2AM members returned to JYP, while [[Lee Chang-min (singer)|Lee Chang-min]] stayed with Big Hit in order to continue with his solo career and as part of the duo [[Homme (band)|Homme]].<ref name=\":2\" /> The year also saw the disbandment of 8Eight after Baek Chan and Joo Hee's contracts with Big Hit ended.\n\nIn May 2015, [[Signal Entertainment Group]], a [[KOSDAQ]]-listed company specializing in artist management and television production, acquired Big Hit through a KR\u20a96 billion [[convertible bond]],<ref name=\"edaily\">{{cite web|url=http://www.edaily.co.kr/news/NewsRead.edy?SCD=JB31&newsid=03450566609368920&DCD=A10103&OutLnkChk=Y|script-title=ko:\uc528\uadf8\ub110\uc5d4\ud130\ud14c\uc778\uba3c\ud2b8\uadf8\ub8f9 \"\ube45\ud788\ud2b8\uc5d4\ud130 CB 60\uc5b5 \uc778\uc218\"|work=eDaily|language=ko|trans-title=Signal Entertainment Group acquires Big Hit Ent for 60 billion \"through CB\"|access-date=February 4, 2016}}</ref> and Lim Jeong-hee parted ways with the agency, following the expiration of her three-year contract.<ref name=\":1\" /> In early 2017, Big Hit ended their stake relationship with Signal Entertainment Group. Big Hit issued a 6 billion won convertible bond Signal Entertainment Group in 2015. After a year, Signal Entertainment Group made a full settlement of the bonds.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.thebell.co.kr/m/newsview.asp?svccode=00&newskey=201702090100018900001148|script-title=ko:\ube45\ud788\ud2b8\uc5d4\ud130, \uc601\uc5c5\uc774\uc775 100\uc5b5 \ub3cc\ud30c\u2026VC '\ud750\ubb47'|work=The Bell|language=ko|access-date=February 28, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/099830.KQ/key-developments/article/3449988|title=Signal Entertainment Group to sell entire shares of entertainment firm for 6.2 bln won|date=October 6, 2016|work=[[Reuters]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170323085540/https://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/099830.KQ/key-developments/article/3449988|archive-date=March 23, 2017|url-status=dead|access-date=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, Homme disbanded after member Changmin's contract came to an end. He left the company to start his own agency, while Lee Hyun continued on as a solo artist.<ref name=\"Lee Hyun now solo\">{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/now/read?oid=311&aid=0000818920|script-title=ko:[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] \uc774\ucc3d\ubbfc, \ube45\ud788\ud2b8\uc640 \uc804\uc18d\uacc4\uc57d \ub9cc\ub8cc \"1\uc778 \uae30\ud68d\uc0ac \uc124\ub9bd\"|date=February 1, 2018|work=Xsports News|language=ko|trans-title=Lee Changmin's contract with Bighit Entertainment expires, \"will start his own agency\"|access-date=August 3, 2019|via=[[Naver]]}}</ref> Later that year in October, Big Hit Entertainment announced that BTS had renewed and extended their contract with them for seven more years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2018/10/17/bts-extend-contracts-with-big-hit-entertainment-until-2026/|title=BTS Extend Contracts With Big Hit Entertainment Until 2026|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=October 17, 2018|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=October 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019, male group [[TXT (band)|Tomorrow X Together]] (TXT) made their debut under Big Hit.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/caitlinkelley/2019/02/06/bts-bighit-tomorrow-x-together-txt-debut/|title=BTS's Label Reveals TOMORROW X TOGETHER Will Debut March 4|last=Kelley|first=Caitlin|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> Former [[Chief business officer|CBO]] Lenzo Yoon was also appointed co-CEO with Bang Si-hyuk,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2019/03/07/big-hit-entertainment-appoints-new-co-ceo-following-rise-of-bts-launch-of-txt/#4189f8e62f79|title=Big Hit Entertainment Appoints New Co-CEO Following Rise Of BTS, Launch Of TXT|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=March 7, 2019|work=[[Forbes]]|access-date=April 19, 2019}}</ref> focusing on the business components of the company while Bang will focus on creative production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=108&aid=0002765749|script-title=ko:\ube45\ud788\ud2b8 '\ubc29\ud0c4 \uc131\uc7a5 \uc8fc\uc5ed' \uc724\uc11d\uc900 \uacf5\ub3d9 \ub300\ud45c\uc774\uc0ac \uc120\uc784|last=Lee|first=Jung-ho|date=March 6, 2019|work=Star News|language=ko|trans-title=Big Hit 'Ballistic Growth Leader' Yoon Seok-jun appointed as co-CEO|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190306111759/https://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=108&aid=0002765749|archive-date=March 6, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=August 3, 2019|via=[[Naver]]}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, the agency acquired [[Source Music]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/caitlinkelley/2019/07/28/btss-label-big-hit-entertainment-acquired-source-music/|title=Big Hit Entertainment, BTS\u2019s Label, Acquires Source Music|last=Kelley|first=Caitlin|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref>\n\n==Company value and investments==\nIn 2007, Big Hit Entertainment was near bankruptcy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-17/mogul-behind-world-s-most-tweeted-about-boy-band-considers-ipo|title=Mogul Behind K-Pop Boy Band BTS Considers IPO}}</ref> Due to the success of early groups [[8Eight]] and [[2AM (band)|2AM]], Bang was able to keep the company afloat{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}} and later created the group [[BTS (band)|BTS]] in 2013. Varying reports consider the current total value of the company at roughly 1T KRW (~891.5M USD).<ref name=\"theinvestor.co.kr\">{{cite news|url=http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20181011000694|title=STIC Investments invests W104b in Big Hit|access-date=2018-10-16|language=en}}</ref> Many consider the company's profit in both the Western and Eastern markets, Big Hit's relatively lenient policies towards their idols' creativity, and innovative music styles to be a cornerstone of the label's success.{{Citation needed|date=July 2019}}\n\nBig Hit Entertainment currently operates as a private company. Bang Si-hyuk remains the largest shareholder of Big Hit  stock. In March 2017, the Korean mobile gaming company [[Netmarble Games|Netmarble]] acquired the second largest percentage of the company, paying a reported 201.4B KRW (191.8M USD) for 25.71%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ajudaily.com/view/20180404164806895|title=Game maker becomes second largest shareholder of BTS' agency}}</ref> The CEO of Netmarble, Bang Joon-Hyuk, and Bang Si-hyuk are cousins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3046607|title=Cousins unite as Netmarble buys stake in Bit Hit|last=Ha|first=Sun-young|date=April 7, 2018|work=Korea JoongAng Daily|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180407131610/http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3046607|archive-date=April 7, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, Big Hit publicized its earnings for the first time, reporting revenue at 92.4B KRW (~82M USD).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20180326000769|title=Expectations high for BTS-backed Big Hit Entertainment\u2019s IPO|last=Lee|first=Ji-Yoo|date=March 26, 2018|work=The Investor|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181107104354/http://www.theinvestor.co.kr/view.php?ud=20180326000769|archive-date=November 7, 2018|url-status=live|access-date=2019-08-03|via=The Korea Herald}}</ref> If entered into an [[Initial public offering|IPO]], the company itself could reach a value of up to 700B KRW (~624M USD), potentially ousting the typically powerful \"Big 3\" companies [[SM Entertainment]], [[JYP Entertainment]], and [[YG Entertainment]]. This would make CEO Bang the richest in the South Korean entertainment business due to his large shareholding position, and leave him with personal ownership value of roughly 350B KRW (~314M USD).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hankyung.com/finance/article/2018032749871|script-title=ko:\uc591\ud604\uc11d \ub118\uc740 \ubc15\uc9c4\uc601\u2026 BTS \ub300\ubc15\uc5d0 \ubc29\uc2dc\ud601 1\uc704|last=Choi|first=Man-soo|date=March 27, 2018|work=Hankyung|language=ko|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190729143619/https://www.hankyung.com/finance/article/2018032749871|archive-date=July 29, 2019|url-status=live|access-date=August 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, Big Hit Entertainment and [[CJ E&M]], another Korean entertainment agency, released information stating plans to create a joint company. Filed under the name Belift, the company will reportedly be split 52% to CJ E&M, and 48% to Big Hit.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/business/2018/07/31/0501000000AEN20180731008500315.html|title=BTS' management agency teams up with CJ affiliate to launch entertainment firm|last=\ubc15\ubcf4\ub78c|date=July 31, 2018|work=Yonhap News Agency|access-date=October 16, 2018}}</ref> The group is set to debut in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2019/03/12/2019031201432.html|title=Entertainment Giants Team up to Manufacture 'Next BTS'|last=Kim|first=Bong-kee|date=March 12, 2019|work=[[The Chosun Ilbo]]|access-date=March 12, 2019}}</ref> CJ E&M's recent foray into idol production television shows such as [[Produce 101]] and Big Hit's growing global auditions are likely to be the venture philosophy of the new company.\n\nIn October 2018, private investment firm [[STIC Investments]] received a reported 12% share of Big Hit Entertainment, an investment of roughly 104B KRW (~93M USD).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paxnet.co.kr/news/mainView?vNewsSetId=5617&articleId=2018101111304401641&wlog_nsise=popularnews|title=\uc2a4\ud2f1\uc778\ubca0\uc2a4\ud2b8, BTS\uc5d0 1040\uc5b5 \ubca0\ud305|date=2018-11-10|website=www.paxnet.co.kr|language=ko|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190803094321/http://www.paxnet.co.kr/news/mainView?vNewsSetId=5617&articleId=2018101111304401641&wlog_nsise=popularnews|archive-date=2019-08-03|url-status=live|access-date=2019-08-03}}</ref> According to the Investor, Big Hit's posted revenue and operating profit of 92.4B (~82M USD) and 32.5B KRW (~29M USD) is expected to return more than double at 230B (~205M USD) and 83B KRW (~74M USD) by the end of 2018.<ref name=\"theinvestor.co.kr\"/> Big Hit was voted best investment company of the year for 2018 at the Korea VC Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&oid=008&aid=0004143145&sid1=001|script-title=ko:\ud55c\uad6d\ubca4\ucc98\ud22c\uc790, \u2018Korea VC Awards 2018\u2019 \uac1c\ucd5c|last=Lee|first=Sang-yeon|date=December 6, 2018|work=Money Today|language=ko|access-date=August 3, 2019|via=[[Naver]]}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2019 the company announced their 2018 audit report. They experienced a 132% increase in sales compared to 2017 making approximately 214.2B KRW, or about US$189.38 million. They had a 97% percent increase in operating profit for the year making 64.1B KRW (US$56.72 million) and a 105% percent increase in net profit making 50.2B KRW (US$44.41 million).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/bts/8503273/bts-label-big-hit-entertainment-record-results-2018|title=BTS Helps Label Big Hit Entertainment to Record Result In 2018|last=Herman|first=Tamar|date=March 20, 2019|work=Billboard|access-date=March 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Subsidiaries and affiliates==\n* beNX<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20190702000587&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=BTS' management company to move into new building|date=July 2, 2019|publisher=The Korea Herald|language=en|accessdate=}}</ref>\n* BELIFT (co-managed by [[CJ E&M]])\n* Superb<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/business/tech/8527708/big-hit-superb-gaming-company-bts|title=BTS' Agency Big Hit Acquires Superb Gaming Company|date=August 19, 2019|publisher=Billboard|language=en|accessdate=}}</ref>\n* [[Source Music]]\n\n==Philanthropy==\nIt was revealed the company donated 30 million won, roughly US$25,500, to the [[Sinking of MV Sewol|Sewol Disaster]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5]\ubc29\ud0c4\uc18c\ub144\ub2e8, \uc138\uc6d4\ud638 \ucc38\uc0ac 416\uac00\uc871\ud611\uc758\ud68c\uc5d0 1\uc5b5\uc6d0 \uae30\ubd80 |url=https://entertain.naver.com/ranking/read?oid=112&aid=0002886804|website=Naver|accessdate=May 23, 2019|language=Korean|date=January 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Artists==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Groups===\n* [[8Eight]]\n* [[BTS (band)|BTS]]\n* [[TXT (band)|TXT]]\n\n===Soloists===\n* [[Lee Hyun]] \n* [[RM (rapper)|RM]]\n* [[Suga (rapper)|Agust D]] \n* [[J-Hope]]\n\n===Actors===\n* [[V (singer)|Kim Tae-hyung]]\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Producers===\n* [[Bang Si-hyuk|\"Hitman\" Bang]]\n* Slow Rabbit<ref>{{cite web|last1=Herman|first1=Tamar|title=7 Factors That Helped Propel BTS To No. 1 On The Billboard 200|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/tamarherman/2018/05/31/7-factors-that-helped-propel-bts-to-no-1-on-the-billboard-200/#6dc3059c12a4|website=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=March 11, 2019|date=May 31, 2018}}</ref>\n* Adora<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=\"Si\u00eau t\u00e2n binh\" TXT: C\u00f3 l\u00e0m n\u00ean kh\u00e1c bi\u1ec7t hay ch\u1ec9 \"g\u00e2y b\u00e3o\" nh\u1edd h\u00e0o quang c\u1ee7a BTS?|url=http://kenh14.vn/sieu-tan-binh-txt-co-lam-nen-khac-biet-hay-chi-gay-bao-nho-hao-quang-cua-bts-20190305102003386.chn|website=kenh14|accessdate=March 11, 2019|language=Vietnamese|date=March 5, 2019}}</ref>\n* Pdogg<ref name =\":5\">{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Arin|title=BTS' team sweeps four awards at 2018 MAMA in Seoul|url=https://www.thejakartapost.com/life/2018/12/11/bts-team-sweeps-four-awards-at-2018-mama-in-seoul.html|website=[[The Jakarta Post]]|accessdate=March 11, 2019|date=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n* Supreme Boi<ref name=\":4\"/>\n* Docskim\n* EL CAPITXN\n* Hissnoise\n\n===Choreographers===\n* Son Sung-deuk<ref name =\":5\"/>\n* Kim Su-bin\n* David DH. Park\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Former artists==\n* [[K.Will]] (2006\u20132007)\n* [[2AM (band)|2AM]] (2010\u20132014, co-managed by [[JYP Entertainment]])\n** Baek Chan (2007-2014)\n** Joo Hee (2007-2014)\n* [[Glam (group)|Glam]] (2012\u20132015, co-managed by Source Music) \n* [[Lim Jeong-hee]] (2012\u20132015)\n* [[Homme (band)|Homme]] (2010\u20132018)\n** [[Lee Chang-min (singer)|Changmin]] (2010\u20132018)<ref name=\"Lee Hyun now solo\"/>\n\n==Discography==\n{{main|Big Hit Entertainment discography}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|https://www.bighitcorp.com/eng/}}\n\n{{Big Hit Entertainment}}\n{{K-pop}}\n\n[[Category:Signal Entertainment Group]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Labels distributed by Kakao M]]\n[[Category:Pop record labels]]\n[[Category:Record labels established in 2005]]\n[[Category:South Korean record labels]]\n[[Category:Talent agencies of South Korea]]\n", "name_user": "Runch Randa18", "label": "safe", "comment": "based on facts", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Hit_Entertainment"}
